export const GENERATED_QUESTIONS_2: SeedQuestion[] = [
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Distinguish Between Fact and Opinion","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence from a brochure about a city aquarium states a fact rather than an opinion?","options":["The shark tank is far more exciting than any other display here.","The jellyfish gallery is the most breathtaking part of the whole building.","The aquarium houses more than 12,000 marine animals across 40 exhibits.","Everyone should visit the aquarium at least once during the summer."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"A fact can be verified or counted. The number of animals and exhibits is measurable and checkable. The other choices use judgment words such as 'most breathtaking,' 'should,' and 'more exciting,' which signal personal opinion."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Distinguish Between Fact and Opinion","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage: 'The new bus route added six stops and now runs every fifteen minutes. In my view, this makes it the best transit decision the council has ever made, and riders clearly agree.' Which statement best identifies the opinion in the passage?","options":["The route is operated by the city council.","The route is the best transit decision the council has ever made.","The route runs every fifteen minutes.","The route added six new stops."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The phrase 'In my view' and the superlative 'best ever' mark a personal judgment that cannot be verified. The number of stops and the frequency of service are measurable facts."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Distinguish Between Fact and Opinion","difficulty":3,"stem":"A nutrition article reads: 'Oats contain soluble fiber called beta-glucan. Studies have measured reductions in cholesterol among people who ate oats daily. Therefore, oatmeal is undeniably the healthiest breakfast a person can choose.' Which sentence shifts the passage from fact to opinion?","options":["Studies have measured reductions in cholesterol among people who ate oats daily.","Therefore, oatmeal is undeniably the healthiest breakfast a person can choose.","Oats contain soluble fiber called beta-glucan.","People in the studies ate oats daily."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The first two sentences report verifiable facts about composition and study results. The final sentence draws an evaluative conclusion using 'undeniably' and the superlative 'healthiest,' which reflects judgment rather than something that can be measured."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Identify Biases and Stereotypes","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence relies on a stereotype?","options":["The office offered a refresher course open to all drivers.","Older drivers in the study renewed their licenses at the local office.","Older drivers are always too slow and confused to handle highways safely.","Some drivers requested larger print on the renewal forms."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"A stereotype applies a fixed, sweeping trait to an entire group. The claim that older drivers are 'always too slow and confused' generalizes about every member of the group. The other sentences describe specific actions without judging the group as a whole."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Identify Biases and Stereotypes","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage: 'Our cleaning product clearly outperforms every competitor on the market. Rival brands are weak, overpriced, and made by companies that do not care about customers.' What does this passage most clearly reveal?","options":["An objective comparison of cleaning products","The author's bias in favor of one product","A balanced review weighing strengths and weaknesses","A neutral summary of laboratory test results"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The author praises one product while dismissing all competitors as weak and uncaring, with no supporting evidence. This one-sided, loaded language reveals a bias rather than an objective or balanced evaluation."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Identify Biases and Stereotypes","difficulty":3,"stem":"A travel writer states: 'People from mountain villages are naturally warm and simple folk who never worry about modern problems.' Which best explains why this statement is problematic?","options":["It compares two different villages without naming them.","It assigns uniform personality traits to an entire group based on where they live.","It cites statistics that cannot be checked by readers.","It provides too many specific details about the villages."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The statement is a stereotype because it assumes that everyone from a region shares the same temperament and concerns. Even seemingly positive labels like 'warm and simple' flatten individual differences and reflect biased thinking."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Interpret the Meaning of Words and Phrases Using Context","difficulty":1,"stem":"Read the sentence: 'The instructions were so terse that the new employee had to ask a coworker to explain each step in detail.' As used here, the word 'terse' most nearly means","options":["long and repetitive","colorful and decorative","brief and lacking detail","friendly and welcoming"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Because the employee needed extra explanation 'in detail,' the instructions must have been short and sparse. 'Terse' means using few words. 'Long and repetitive' is the opposite of what the context requires."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Interpret the Meaning of Words and Phrases Using Context","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the sentence: 'After the storm, the volunteers worked to salvage whatever furniture had not been ruined by the flood.' As used in this sentence, 'salvage' most nearly means","options":["to repaint and decorate","to rescue or save from loss","to throw away","to sell at a discount"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The volunteers are saving furniture that 'had not been ruined,' so 'salvage' means to recover or save something from damage. The contrast with the ruined items shows they are preserving what remains."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Interpret the Meaning of Words and Phrases Using Context","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the sentence: 'The committee's support for the proposal was only nominal; although they voted yes, they provided no funding and attended none of the planning meetings.' As used here, 'nominal' most nearly means","options":["expensive and demanding","carefully measured and exact","in name only, not in substance","enthusiastic and complete"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The semicolon introduces an explanation: the committee voted yes but did nothing else. 'Nominal' here means existing in name but not in real effect. 'Nominal' can also mean 'small in amount,' but the context about lack of action forces the 'in name only' sense."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Use Dictionary and Library Entries","difficulty":1,"stem":"A dictionary page has the guide words 'marble' and 'mark.' Which word would appear on this page?","options":["manatee","martyr","margin","marsh"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Words on the page fall alphabetically between 'marble' and 'mark.' 'Margin' (m-a-r-g) comes after 'marble' (m-a-r-b) and before 'mark' (m-a-r-k). 'Manatee' comes before 'marble,' and 'marsh' and 'martyr' come after 'mark.'"},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Use Dictionary and Library Entries","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read this dictionary entry: 'current (adj.) 1. belonging to the present time. 2. (n.) a continuous flow of water, air, or electricity. 3. (n.) the general movement or tendency of opinion.' In the sentence 'The current of public feeling turned against the new tax,' which definition applies?","options":["Definition 2","Definition 1","Definition 3","None of the definitions"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"In the sentence, 'current' refers to the trend or movement of public opinion, which matches definition 3. It is used as a noun describing the general direction of feeling, not the present time or a flow of water."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Use Dictionary and Library Entries","difficulty":2,"stem":"Using a library catalog, a student wants the most recent and frequently updated information about current vaccination guidelines. Which source is the best choice?","options":["A biography of a nineteenth-century physician","A novel set in a hospital during a past epidemic","A regularly updated government public health website","A printed encyclopedia published twelve years ago"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Current guidelines change often, so the student needs a source that is updated frequently and authoritative. A government public health website is regularly revised. The encyclopedia is outdated, and the novel and biography are not reference sources for current guidelines."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Evaluate the Author's Purpose in a Given Text","difficulty":1,"stem":"A pamphlet reads: 'Step 1: Unplug the device. Step 2: Remove the back panel using a screwdriver. Step 3: Replace the worn battery and reattach the panel.' What is the author's primary purpose?","options":["To instruct readers how to complete a task","To express personal feelings about repairs","To entertain readers with a funny story","To persuade readers to buy a new device"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The numbered steps explain how to perform a procedure, so the purpose is to instruct. There is no persuasion, narrative, or emotional expression in the text."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Evaluate the Author's Purpose in a Given Text","difficulty":2,"stem":"An essay concludes: 'For all these reasons, the town must approve funding for the new library this year. Contact your council member today and demand action.' What is the author's main purpose?","options":["To entertain readers with a personal anecdote","To describe the appearance of the library","To persuade readers to support library funding","To explain how libraries organize their books"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The author argues that the town 'must approve funding' and urges readers to 'demand action,' which are persuasive moves meant to influence opinion and behavior. The goal is to convince, not merely describe or explain."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Evaluate the Author's Purpose in a Given Text","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the passage: 'Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants convert sunlight, water, and carbon dioxide into glucose and oxygen. This reaction occurs in the chloroplasts and forms the base of most food chains.' What is the author's primary purpose?","options":["To criticize scientists who study photosynthesis","To recount a personal experience studying plants","To convince readers that plants are superior to animals","To inform readers about how a biological process works"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The passage explains a process using neutral, factual language and technical terms. Its purpose is to inform readers about how photosynthesis works, not to persuade, narrate, or criticize."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Recognize Text Structure","difficulty":1,"stem":"Read the passage: 'First, gather your ingredients. Next, mix the dry items in one bowl. Then, add the wet items. Finally, bake the batter for thirty minutes.' Which text structure does this passage use?","options":["Sequence or chronological order","Cause and effect","Compare and contrast","Problem and solution"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The signal words 'first,' 'next,' 'then,' and 'finally' show that the steps are arranged in time order. This is a sequence or chronological structure."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Recognize Text Structure","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage: 'Many downtown shops were losing customers to online sellers. To address this, the merchants' association launched a weekend market and a free delivery service, which brought shoppers back to the district.' Which text structure best describes this passage?","options":["Problem and solution","Compare and contrast","Chronological order","Spatial description"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The passage first presents a problem, shops losing customers, and then describes the actions taken to fix it and the result. This is a problem-and-solution structure."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Recognize Text Structure","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the passage: 'Both electric and gasoline cars provide reliable transportation. However, electric cars produce no tailpipe emissions and run quietly, whereas gasoline cars can be refueled in minutes and travel farther between fill-ups.' Which text structure does the author use?","options":["Cause and effect","Problem and solution","Compare and contrast","Sequence"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The passage examines similarities and differences between two types of cars, using signal words like 'both,' 'however,' and 'whereas.' This is a compare-and-contrast structure."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Analyze Types of Writing","difficulty":1,"stem":"Read the passage: 'The old lighthouse stood at the edge of the cliff, its white tower streaked with rust. Waves crashed against the jagged rocks below, sending cold spray into the salty air.' Which type of writing does this passage represent?","options":["Expository","Descriptive","Persuasive","Narrative"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The passage uses sensory details, such as the rust-streaked tower, crashing waves, and salty air, to paint a vivid picture of a scene. This is descriptive writing, which appeals to the senses rather than arguing or telling a story of events."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Analyze Types of Writing","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage: 'As soon as the bell rang, Marcus grabbed his backpack and sprinted to the parking lot. He had only ten minutes to reach the bus station, and his heart pounded with every step.' Which type of writing is this?","options":["Persuasive","Expository","Narrative","Technical"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The passage tells a story about a character, Marcus, and a sequence of events, including his actions and feelings. Telling a story with characters and events is the defining feature of narrative writing."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Analyze Types of Writing","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the passage: 'The water cycle consists of three main stages. During evaporation, the sun heats water into vapor. During condensation, the vapor cools and forms clouds. During precipitation, water falls back to the earth as rain or snow.' Which type of writing best describes this passage?","options":["Narrative, because it tells a story over time","Expository, because it explains a process with facts","Persuasive, because it urges the reader to act","Descriptive, because it focuses on sensory imagery"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The passage explains the stages of a process using clear, factual information without arguing a position or telling a story. Writing that informs or explains is expository."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Evaluate the Author's Point of View or Perspective in a Given Text","difficulty":1,"stem":"Read the passage: 'I have lived in this neighborhood for thirty years, and I can tell you that the new park has changed our lives for the better. My grandchildren now have a safe place to play.' From what point of view is this passage written?","options":["Second-person","First-person","Third-person objective","Third-person omniscient"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The author uses 'I,' 'my,' and 'our,' speaking from personal experience as a resident. The use of first-person pronouns shows this is written from the author's own first-person point of view."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Evaluate the Author's Point of View or Perspective in a Given Text","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage: 'As a nurse who has worked night shifts for a decade, I believe hospitals must rethink scheduling. Exhausted staff make more mistakes, and patients deserve caregivers who are rested and alert.' Which best describes the author's perspective?","options":["A neutral observer with no stake in the issue","A patient complaining about hospital food","An experienced nurse advocating for schedule changes","A hospital administrator defending current policies"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The author identifies as 'a nurse who has worked night shifts for a decade' and argues that hospitals 'must rethink scheduling.' The perspective is that of an experienced nurse advocating for change based on firsthand knowledge."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"craft-structure","subtopic":"Evaluate the Author's Point of View or Perspective in a Given Text","difficulty":3,"stem":"Two writers describe the same factory closing. Writer A states: 'The closure freed valuable land for a modern housing development that the city badly needed.' Writer B states: 'The closure stripped hundreds of families of steady wages they had relied on for generations.' Which statement best describes the difference in their points of view?","options":["Writer A emphasizes economic loss, while Writer B emphasizes new opportunity.","Both writers share the same view about the closure's effects.","Writer A focuses on benefits of the closure, while Writer B focuses on its harm to workers.","Neither writer expresses any point of view about the closure."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Writer A frames the closing positively by highlighting land for needed housing, while Writer B frames it negatively by stressing lost wages for families. Their differing emphases reveal opposite perspectives on the same event."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Use Evidence From the Text to Make Predictions, Inferences, and Draw Conclusions","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nMarisol had repaired clocks in the same shop for thirty years. Lately she noticed that customers brought in fewer mechanical watches and more smartwatches she could not service. Each month she sold a few more batteries and fixed a few fewer gears. She began keeping the front display case stocked with charging cables instead of winding keys, and she enrolled in an online course on phone screen replacement.\n\nWhich conclusion is best supported by the passage?","options":["Marisol plans to close her shop within the year because business has collapsed.","Marisol is adapting her business in response to a shift in the kind of devices customers use.","Marisol prefers smartwatches to mechanical watches for personal reasons.","Marisol's customers have stopped coming to her shop entirely."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Restocking the case with cables and enrolling in a repair course are evidence that Marisol is changing her offerings to match what customers now bring in. The passage gives no evidence she will close (she is investing in new skills), no statement of personal preference, and customers still come (she sells batteries), so the other options overreach or contradict the text."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Use Evidence From the Text to Make Predictions, Inferences, and Draw Conclusions","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nThe trail guide warned the group that the river crossing ahead was usually ankle-deep but rose quickly after rain. As the hikers approached, they heard a low roar, and the guide stopped to study the muddy, churning water sliding over the marked stepping stones. She unclipped the rope from her pack and asked everyone to wait while she scouted upstream.\n\nBased on the passage, what will the guide most likely do next?","options":["Hand the rope to a hiker and let the group cross on its own.","Look for a safer place to cross because the usual crossing appears dangerous.","Turn the group around and cancel the hike permanently.","Lead the group straight across the marked stepping stones without delay."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The muddy churning water over the stones, the roar, and the guide unclipping her rope and scouting upstream all signal she judges the normal crossing unsafe and is seeking an alternative. Crossing the stones now contradicts her caution, canceling permanently overreaches (she only scouts), and handing off the rope contradicts her taking charge."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Use Evidence From the Text to Make Predictions, Inferences, and Draw Conclusions","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nDevon arrived at the interview twenty minutes early and sat reviewing a folder of notes. When the receptionist offered him coffee, he declined, saying he did not want to risk a spill on his shirt. He had pressed the shirt the night before and laid out his shoes by the door. In the waiting room he silently rehearsed answers to questions he had written on index cards.\n\nWhich inference about Devon is best supported by the passage?","options":["Devon has prepared carefully and wants to make a strong impression.","Devon expects to be offered the job before he even interviews.","Devon dislikes coffee and avoids it in all situations.","Devon is overqualified for the position he is interviewing for."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Arriving early, pressing the shirt, laying out shoes, declining coffee to avoid a stain, and rehearsing with index cards are all evidence of careful preparation aimed at a good impression. Nothing addresses his qualifications, his general feelings about coffee (he avoids it here for a specific reason), or his expectations of an offer."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Compare and Contrast the Themes Expressed in One or More Texts","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read both passages and answer the question.\n\nPassage 1: The old fisherman said the sea gives nothing for free. Every fish in the net, he told his grandson, is paid for with patience, cold hands, and hours of waiting in the dark before dawn. What you earn that way, he said, you never throw back.\n\nPassage 2: Mara won the lottery on a whim, buying a ticket with spare change at the gas station. Within two years the money was gone, spent on things she could barely remember. She often said she had never missed what came so easily.\n\nWhich theme do both passages share?","options":["People who plan carefully always end up wealthier than those who do not.","Hard physical labor is the only honorable way to make a living.","Things gained through effort are valued more than things gained easily.","Luck is more reliable than patience in providing for a family."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Passage 1 shows the fisherman prizing fish earned through patience and never throwing them back; Passage 2 shows Mara not valuing money that came easily and quickly losing it. Together they convey that effortful gains are valued more. The other options either overstate (only honorable way, always wealthier) or reverse the passages' point about luck."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Compare and Contrast the Themes Expressed in One or More Texts","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read both passages and answer the question.\n\nPassage 1: When the storm tore the roof off the community hall, the whole town showed up the next morning with hammers and ladders. By dusk the hall stood again. No one had organized it; people simply came because the hall belonged to all of them.\n\nPassage 2: The lighthouse keeper lived alone for forty years, trusting only the lamp and his own two hands. When the supply boat failed to come, he rationed his food and told himself, as he always had, that a man must depend on no one.\n\nHow do the themes of the two passages differ?","options":["Passage 1 celebrates communal effort, while Passage 2 emphasizes self-reliance.","Passage 1 warns against trusting others, while Passage 2 praises teamwork.","Passage 1 focuses on grief, while Passage 2 focuses on ambition.","Both passages argue that hard work is pointless without reward."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Passage 1 stresses that the town came together unprompted to rebuild a shared hall (community), while Passage 2 stresses the keeper's insistence on depending on no one (self-reliance). Option 2 reverses the passages, and the others introduce themes (futility of work, grief, ambition) absent from the texts."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Compare and Contrast the Themes Expressed in One or More Texts","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read both passages and answer the question.\n\nPassage 1: The inventor kept a wall of failed sketches. Visitors thought it a strange decoration, but she insisted each crossed-out design had taught her something the finished machine could not have. Failure, she said, was simply information arriving early.\n\nPassage 2: The young chess champion lost only once, and he never spoke of that game again. He removed the record from his shelf and refused to analyze it, certain that dwelling on a loss could only weaken him.\n\nWhich statement best compares the themes of the two passages?","options":["Both passages claim that talent matters more than effort in achieving success.","Both passages argue that failure should be hidden from others to preserve reputation.","Both passages concern how a person responds to failure, but they reach opposite conclusions about its value.","Passage 1 is about teamwork, while Passage 2 is about isolation."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Both texts center on a response to failure: the inventor treats it as valuable information, while the champion treats it as something to erase. They share the subject but draw opposite conclusions about failure's worth. The other options misread one or both passages (the inventor displays failure rather than hiding it; neither discusses talent versus effort or teamwork)."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Evaluate an Argument","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nA columnist writes: \"Our city should ban all food trucks downtown. Last summer a single food truck was cited for a health violation. Clearly, mobile vendors cannot be trusted to keep food safe, and the only way to protect residents is to remove them from the streets entirely.\"\n\nWhich is the strongest criticism of the columnist's argument?","options":["The argument uses emotional language that upsets downtown residents.","The argument fails to mention how many restaurants also had health violations.","The argument draws a sweeping conclusion about all food trucks from a single cited vendor.","The argument does not explain how food trucks obtain their permits."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The columnist generalizes from one citation to the claim that all mobile vendors cannot be trusted, an overgeneralization (hasty generalization). That logical flaw is the core weakness. Restaurant violations and permit processes are tangential, and the tone, while strong, is not the structural problem with the reasoning."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Evaluate an Argument","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nAn advertisement reads: \"Nine out of ten dentists surveyed recommend BrightMint toothpaste. Switch today and give your family the protection the experts choose.\" The fine print notes that the dentists were asked only whether they would recommend BrightMint or no toothpaste at all.\n\nWhy does the fine print weaken the advertisement's claim?","options":["It shows that fewer than nine out of ten dentists actually responded.","It reveals the dentists were not comparing BrightMint to other toothpastes, so the survey does not show BrightMint is better than competitors.","It proves that the dentists were paid by a competing toothpaste company.","It indicates that the toothpaste has never been tested on families."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The ad implies dentists chose BrightMint over rivals, but the fine print shows the only alternative offered was no toothpaste, so the survey cannot support a claim of superiority over competitors. The other options assert facts (payment, low response, untested) the passage never states."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Evaluate an Argument","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nA student argues: \"The school should require every student to join a sports team. Studies show that students who play sports tend to have higher grades. Therefore, requiring sports will raise everyone's grades.\"\n\nWhich assumption must be true for the student's argument to hold?","options":["The school has enough money to fund additional teams.","Higher grades are the most important goal a school can have.","Every student already enjoys playing at least one sport.","Playing sports causes higher grades rather than merely occurring alongside them."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The argument leaps from a correlation (sports players tend to have higher grades) to a causal claim that requiring sports will raise grades. For that to work, the argument must assume sports actually cause the higher grades. Enjoyment, funding, and the priority of grades are practical or value concerns, not the logical gap the conclusion depends on."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Identify Primary Sources","difficulty":2,"stem":"A historian is researching the experience of soldiers during a 1918 battle. Which of the following would serve as a primary source?","options":["A documentary produced in 2015 about the war.","An encyclopedia entry describing the battle's causes.","A letter written by a soldier to his family during the battle in 1918.","A textbook chapter published in 2010 summarizing the battle."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"A primary source is a firsthand, original record created by someone who experienced the event. The soldier's letter written during the battle is such a record. The textbook, documentary, and encyclopedia entry are secondary sources that analyze or summarize the event after the fact."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Identify Primary Sources","difficulty":3,"stem":"A nursing student is studying how a new hand-washing protocol affected infection rates at a hospital. Which source would be considered a primary source for this research?","options":["A news report describing the hospital's findings to the public.","A nursing textbook's section on infection control practices.","A review article in a journal summarizing several hand-washing studies.","The original dataset of recorded infection counts collected by the hospital ward during the study."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The raw infection-count dataset recorded directly during the study is original, firsthand evidence, making it a primary source. A review article, a news report, and a textbook all interpret or summarize the data secondhand and are secondary sources."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Identify Primary Sources","difficulty":2,"stem":"A journalist is writing about a city council meeting that took place last night. Which item is a primary source about what happened at the meeting?","options":["A neighbor's secondhand account of what a friend told them about the meeting.","A blog post analyzing the meeting written by a political commentator.","The official audio recording of the council meeting.","A magazine retrospective published a year later about the council's decisions."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The official audio recording captures the meeting directly as it occurred, making it a primary source. The blog analysis and the year-later retrospective interpret events after the fact, and the secondhand neighbor account is not a direct record of the meeting itself."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Evaluate and Integrate Data From Multiple Sources Across Various Formats","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the text and table, then answer the question.\n\nText: A community library tracked attendance at its weekly evening programs. The director noted that programs offering free childcare consistently drew larger crowds than those without it.\n\nTable: Average Weekly Attendance\nProgram | Free Childcare? | Attendance\nBook Club | No | 18\nFamily Movie | Yes | 52\nLanguage Class | Yes | 47\nLecture Series | No | 21\n\nWhich conclusion is best supported by both the text and the table?","options":["Free childcare is the only factor that determines program attendance.","Programs that offered free childcare had higher attendance than those that did not.","The Book Club would attract more than 50 people if it met in the morning.","The Lecture Series will be canceled because of low attendance."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The table shows the two programs with free childcare (52 and 47) drew more than the two without it (18 and 21), and the text states the same pattern, so option 1 is supported by both. The other options overreach: nothing addresses morning timing, the data does not establish childcare as the only factor, and no cancellation is mentioned."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Evaluate and Integrate Data From Multiple Sources Across Various Formats","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the text and table, then answer the question.\n\nText: A clinic measured the average wait time for patients before and after hiring a second receptionist in March. Staff hoped the change would reduce delays.\n\nTable: Average Patient Wait Time (minutes)\nMonth | Wait Time\nFebruary | 34\nMarch | 29\nApril | 22\nMay | 21\n\nWhich statement is best supported by combining the text and the table?","options":["Wait times will reach zero minutes by the end of the year.","Average wait times decreased in the months after the second receptionist was hired.","Patients were more satisfied with the clinic after March.","The clinic saw more patients in May than in February."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The text says the receptionist was hired in March, and the table shows wait times falling from 34 in February to 29, 22, and 21 in the following months, supporting option 1. The table gives no data on reaching zero, patient volume, or satisfaction, so the other options are unsupported."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"integration-knowledge","subtopic":"Evaluate and Integrate Data From Multiple Sources Across Various Formats","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the two sources, then answer the question.\n\nSource 1 (text): A gardener recorded how well three tomato varieties grew in her shaded backyard, where plants receive only about four hours of sun per day.\n\nSource 2 (table): Tomato Yield in the Shaded Garden\nVariety | Recommended Sun | Pounds Harvested\nSungold | Full sun | 3\nBush Early | Partial sun | 11\nBeefsteak | Full sun | 2\n\nWhich conclusion is best supported by integrating both sources?","options":["Beefsteak tomatoes are the worst-tasting of the three varieties.","Sungold tomatoes cannot grow in any amount of shade.","All three varieties would yield equally in a sunnier garden.","The variety suited to partial sun outproduced the full-sun varieties in the shaded garden."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Source 1 establishes the garden is shaded with only four hours of sun, and the table shows Bush Early (recommended for partial sun) harvested 11 pounds versus 3 and 2 for the full-sun varieties, supporting option 1. Taste is never mentioned, the data does not address a sunnier garden, and Sungold still produced 3 pounds, so it did grow in shade."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Identify the Topic, Main Idea, and Supporting Details","difficulty":1,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nThe axolotl, a salamander native to a single lake system in Mexico, has fascinated scientists for one striking reason: it can regrow lost body parts. A severed limb returns within weeks, complete with bone, muscle, and nerves. Researchers have even observed the axolotl rebuild portions of its heart and spinal cord. Because of these abilities, laboratories around the world now breed the animal to study how regeneration works.\n\nWhat is the main idea of this passage?","options":["Laboratories around the world breed many kinds of salamanders.","The axolotl's remarkable ability to regrow body parts makes it valuable to scientists.","The axolotl lives only in a single lake system in Mexico.","A severed axolotl limb takes several weeks to grow back."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The passage centers on the axolotl's regeneration ability and why it draws scientific interest; the other options are supporting details or narrower facts rather than the overall point."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Identify the Topic, Main Idea, and Supporting Details","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nMany people assume that bamboo is a kind of tree, but it is actually a grass. Unlike trees, which add new wood in rings each year, bamboo reaches its full height in a single growing season and never thickens afterward. Its hollow, jointed stems give it the strength to sway in storms that would snap rigid trunks. Some species can grow nearly a meter in a single day.\n\nWhich sentence best states the topic of the passage?","options":["The passage is about the fastest-growing plants on Earth.","The passage is about how bamboo differs from trees and grows.","The passage is about storms that snap rigid tree trunks.","The passage is about the yearly growth rings of trees."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The topic is the subject the passage covers as a whole: bamboo, its nature as a grass, and how it grows and differs from trees. The other choices name details or unrelated subjects."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Identify the Topic, Main Idea, and Supporting Details","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nThe lighthouse keeper's job was once one of the loneliest in the world. Stationed for months on rocky islands, keepers trimmed wicks, polished lenses, and wound the heavy clockwork that turned the light. They kept detailed logs of passing ships and changing weather. When automation arrived in the twentieth century, machines took over these tasks, and the last keepers were sent home.\n\nWhich detail from the passage supports the idea that the keeper's work was demanding?","options":["Automation arrived in the twentieth century.","Lighthouses were built on rocky islands.","Keepers trimmed wicks, polished lenses, and wound heavy clockwork.","The last keepers were eventually sent home."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The list of physical, repeated tasks shows the work was demanding. The other options describe the end of the profession or its setting, not its difficulty."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Summarize a Multi-Paragraph Text","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nWhen a city decides to plant trees along its streets, the benefits go beyond appearance. Mature trees shade pavement and buildings, lowering summer temperatures and reducing the energy needed for cooling. Their leaves trap dust and absorb some pollutants from the air.\n\nHowever, street trees also bring costs. Roots can crack sidewalks and clog pipes, and falling limbs may damage cars or wires. City budgets must cover pruning, leaf removal, and occasional replacement.\n\nWhich choice best summarizes the passage?","options":["Street trees lower summer temperatures and reduce the energy needed to cool buildings nearby.","Tree roots crack sidewalks and clog pipes, so cities should avoid planting trees.","Street trees offer real benefits such as cooling and cleaner air, but they also create maintenance costs and hazards a city must manage.","Cities plant trees mainly to make their streets look more attractive to residents."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"A good summary captures both paragraphs: the benefits and the costs. The other options reflect only one side or a minor point."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Summarize a Multi-Paragraph Text","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nFor centuries, sailors navigated by dead reckoning, estimating their position from speed, heading, and time elapsed. The method worked reasonably well over short distances but accumulated errors on long voyages, sometimes placing ships hundreds of miles from where their crews believed they were.\n\nThe invention of the marine chronometer changed this. By keeping accurate time at sea, the device let navigators calculate longitude precisely. Voyages grew safer, and trade routes that had once been gambles became dependable.\n\nWhich choice best summarizes the passage?","options":["Dead reckoning left ships dangerously imprecise on long voyages, but the accurate timekeeping of the marine chronometer made navigation reliable.","Long sea voyages were once gambles because trade routes were unpredictable and risky.","Sailors estimated position from speed, heading, and elapsed time using a method called dead reckoning.","The marine chronometer kept accurate time and helped sailors find their longitude at sea."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The summary must combine the problem (imprecise dead reckoning) with the solution (the chronometer making navigation reliable). Each other option covers only part of the text."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Summarize a Multi-Paragraph Text","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nHoneybees communicate the location of food through movement. A scout that finds a rich patch of flowers returns to the hive and performs a looping pattern often called a waggle dance. The angle of the dance relative to the sun indicates direction, and its duration signals distance.\n\nThis silent language lets a colony direct hundreds of workers to the same source without any of them having seen it. In effect, one bee's discovery becomes the whole hive's knowledge.\n\nWhich choice best summarizes the passage?","options":["A scout bee performs a looping movement when it returns to the hive after finding flowers.","Honeybees live in colonies that contain hundreds of worker bees and scouts.","Through a waggle dance that encodes direction and distance, a single scout bee can guide the entire colony to a food source.","The angle of a bee's dance relative to the sun tells other bees which way to fly."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The summary ties the mechanism (the dance encoding direction and distance) to its effect (guiding the colony). The other options state isolated details."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Infer Logical Conclusions From a Text","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nThe town's only bakery closed at noon every Wednesday so the owner could deliver bread to the three restaurants under contract. On those afternoons, the shelves out front stayed empty, and a handwritten sign in the window listed the regular hours for the rest of the week.\n\nBased on the passage, which conclusion is best supported?","options":["The bakery was closed every afternoon throughout the week.","The owner disliked serving walk-in customers on busy days.","A customer who arrived at the bakery at 2 p.m. on a Wednesday would not be able to buy bread there.","The bakery earned most of its income from the three restaurant contracts."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Since the bakery closed at noon on Wednesdays, a 2 p.m. Wednesday visitor could not buy there. The other options claim motives or facts (income share, dislike, daily closure) the passage does not support."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Infer Logical Conclusions From a Text","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nMarisol noticed that the houseplants nearest the north window grew tall and pale, stretching their stems toward the glass, while the same kind of plant on the sunny south sill stayed short and deep green. She moved one of the pale plants to the south sill, and within two weeks its new leaves came in darker and its stems thickened.\n\nWhich conclusion is best supported by the passage?","options":["Plants placed near windows always grow taller than other plants.","Deep green plants need less water than pale, stretched ones.","The north window in Marisol's home was permanently broken.","The amount of light a plant receives affects its color and growth shape."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The contrast between low-light and high-light plants, plus the change after moving one, points to light affecting color and growth. The other options overgeneralize or introduce unsupported claims."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Infer Logical Conclusions From a Text","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nThe museum's new exhibit allowed visitors to touch replicas of ancient pottery while the genuine artifacts remained behind glass nearby. Staff reported that fingerprints on the display cases dropped sharply after the replicas were added, and fewer guards were needed to remind people not to lean on the glass.\n\nWhich conclusion is best supported by the passage?","options":["Guards at the museum were no longer necessary at all.","The museum planned to remove the genuine artifacts from display.","Visitors preferred the replicas to the genuine ancient pottery.","Offering touchable replicas reduced visitors' attempts to touch the real artifacts."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Fewer fingerprints and fewer reminders after adding replicas suggest the replicas satisfied the urge to touch. The other options state preferences or plans the passage does not establish."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Demonstrate Comprehension of Written Directions","difficulty":1,"stem":"Read the directions and answer the question.\n\nTo reset the thermostat: First, slide the power switch on the right side to OFF and wait ten seconds. Next, press and hold the MENU button until the screen blinks twice. Then release the button and slide the power switch back to ON. Finally, set your preferred temperature using the arrow keys.\n\nAccording to the directions, what should you do immediately after the screen blinks twice?","options":["Slide the power switch to OFF.","Set the temperature with the arrow keys.","Release the MENU button.","Wait ten seconds."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The directions say to hold MENU until the screen blinks twice, then release the button. Setting temperature and sliding power to OFF occur at other steps."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Demonstrate Comprehension of Written Directions","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the directions and answer the question.\n\nBefore applying the wood stain, sand the surface with the grain using medium-grit paper, then wipe away all dust with a damp cloth and let the wood dry completely. Do not apply stain to a damp surface. Stir the stain gently; never shake the can, as shaking creates bubbles that mar the finish. Apply a thin coat with a brush, following the grain.\n\nAccording to the directions, why should you stir rather than shake the stain?","options":["Stirring helps the wood dry faster.","Shaking creates bubbles that ruin the finish.","Stirring sands the wood with the grain.","Shaking removes dust from the surface."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The directions explicitly state that shaking creates bubbles that mar the finish, which is why stirring is preferred. The other options confuse separate steps."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Demonstrate Comprehension of Written Directions","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the directions and answer the question.\n\nLab safety procedure for spilled acid: If acid contacts skin, immediately flush the area with cool running water for at least fifteen minutes. Remove any contaminated clothing while flushing. Do not apply ointment or neutralizing chemicals to the skin. After flushing, notify the lab supervisor and complete an incident report.\n\nAccording to the procedure, which action is prohibited after acid contacts the skin?","options":["Notifying the lab supervisor.","Applying a neutralizing chemical to the skin.","Removing contaminated clothing.","Flushing the area with cool running water."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The procedure says not to apply ointment or neutralizing chemicals to the skin. Flushing, removing clothing, and notifying the supervisor are all required actions."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Locate Specific Information in a Text","difficulty":1,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nThe community pool opens for the season on May 24 and closes on September 2. Lap swimming is reserved for the early morning hours, from 6:00 a.m. to 8:00 a.m. on weekdays. Open swim runs from 10:00 a.m. to 7:00 p.m. daily. Swim lessons for children are held on Saturday mornings beginning at 9:00 a.m.\n\nAccording to the passage, when is lap swimming available?","options":["From May 24 to September 2 at all hours.","From 6:00 a.m. to 8:00 a.m. on weekdays.","On Saturday mornings at 9:00 a.m.","From 10:00 a.m. to 7:00 p.m. daily."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The passage states lap swimming is from 6:00 to 8:00 a.m. on weekdays. The other times refer to open swim, lessons, or the overall season."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Locate Specific Information in a Text","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nThe Pacific giant octopus typically weighs about 33 pounds, though unusually large individuals have reached over 100 pounds. It lives in the cold coastal waters of the northern Pacific, often hiding in dens among rocks. A female lays tens of thousands of eggs at once and guards them without eating until they hatch, after which she dies.\n\nAccording to the passage, what does the female octopus do while guarding her eggs?","options":["She weighs over 100 pounds.","She lays a second batch of eggs.","She does not eat.","She moves the eggs to deeper water."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The passage states the female guards the eggs without eating until they hatch. The weight figure describes rare individuals, and the other actions are not mentioned."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Locate Specific Information in a Text","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nThe Riverside branch library offers several services beyond lending books. The first floor houses a quiet reading room and a bank of public computers, available without a reservation. The second floor contains study rooms that groups may reserve up to two weeks in advance. The basement level holds the local history archive, open only on Thursdays and by appointment.\n\nAccording to the passage, where is the local history archive located?","options":["In the second-floor study rooms.","On the basement level.","In the first-floor reading room.","At the bank of public computers."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The passage states the local history archive is in the basement level. The first and second floors hold other services."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Identify Information From a Printed Communication","difficulty":1,"stem":"Read the notice and answer the question.\n\nNOTICE TO RESIDENTS\nWater service to Building C will be temporarily shut off on Tuesday, June 30, from 9:00 a.m. to 1:00 p.m. so that crews can replace a corroded main valve. Please store drinking water in advance. Service to Buildings A and B will not be affected. We apologize for the inconvenience.\n- Greenfield Property Management\n\nAccording to the notice, why will the water be shut off?","options":["To replace a corroded main valve.","To clean the drinking water supply.","To repair water service in Buildings A and B.","Because residents failed to store water."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The notice states the shutoff is so crews can replace a corroded main valve. Buildings A and B are explicitly unaffected, and the other reasons are not given."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Identify Information From a Printed Communication","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the email and answer the question.\n\nTo: All Volunteers\nFrom: Shelter Coordinator\nSubject: Schedule Change for the Adoption Fair\n\nHi everyone. The adoption fair has been moved from Saturday to Sunday because of the forecasted storm. Setup now begins at 8:00 a.m. Sunday in the east parking lot. If you signed up for a Saturday shift, your shift carries over to the same time on Sunday. Please reply by Friday if you can no longer attend.\n\nAccording to the email, what should a volunteer do if they can no longer attend?","options":["Reply by Friday.","Sign up for a new Sunday shift.","Report to the west parking lot.","Arrive at 8:00 a.m. Saturday."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The email asks volunteers to reply by Friday if they can no longer attend. The fair moved to Sunday in the east lot, and shifts carry over automatically."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Identify Information From a Printed Communication","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the product label and answer the question.\n\nORALEASE THROAT SPRAY\nDirections: Adults and children 12 years and older, spray twice into the throat every two hours as needed. Do not exceed 8 doses in 24 hours. Children under 12: ask a doctor. Stop use and ask a doctor if sore throat lasts more than 2 days or is accompanied by fever.\nWarnings: Do not use if seal under cap is broken.\n\nAccording to the label, what is the maximum number of doses an adult may take in one day?","options":["2 doses.","8 doses.","12 doses.","24 doses."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The label states not to exceed 8 doses in 24 hours. The number 2 refers to sprays per dose or days of use, and 12 is the minimum age."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Identify Information From a Graphic","difficulty":2,"stem":"A bar graph titled 'Monthly Rainfall (in inches), Maple County' shows the following values: January 2.1, February 1.8, March 3.4, April 4.6, May 5.2, June 3.0. The vertical axis measures inches of rainfall, and the horizontal axis lists the months January through June.\n\nAccording to the graph, which month had the highest rainfall?","options":["January","May","April","March"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"May shows 5.2 inches, the largest value among the listed months. April (4.6) is second highest."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Identify Information From a Graphic","difficulty":2,"stem":"A nutrition table for one cup of cooked lentils lists the following: Calories 230, Protein 18 g, Dietary Fiber 16 g, Total Fat 1 g, Iron 37% of the Daily Value, Folate 90% of the Daily Value.\n\nAccording to the table, which nutrient meets the highest percentage of the Daily Value in one cup of lentils?","options":["Dietary Fiber","Iron","Protein","Folate"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Folate is listed at 90% of the Daily Value, higher than iron at 37%. Protein and fiber are given in grams, not as a percentage of the Daily Value."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Identify Information From a Graphic","difficulty":3,"stem":"A line graph titled 'Library Visitors per Day' tracks two lines across one week. The 'Adults' line reads: Mon 120, Tue 110, Wed 140, Thu 130, Fri 160, Sat 200. The 'Children' line reads: Mon 40, Tue 35, Wed 60, Thu 50, Fri 70, Sat 150.\n\nOn which day was the gap between adult and child visitors the smallest?","options":["Wednesday","Friday","Saturday","Monday"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Saturday's gap is 200 minus 150 = 50, smaller than Friday's 90, Monday's 80, and Wednesday's 80. So Saturday has the smallest difference."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Interpret Events in a Sequence","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nDeshawn's morning followed its usual order. He woke to his alarm at six, then laced up his shoes for a short run around the block. When he returned, he showered and ate a bowl of oatmeal. Only after rinsing his bowl did he sit down to review his notes for the chemistry exam scheduled that afternoon.\n\nAccording to the passage, what did Deshawn do immediately before reviewing his notes?","options":["He laced up his shoes.","He woke to his alarm.","He rinsed his bowl.","He took a shower."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The passage says only after rinsing his bowl did he sit down to review notes, so rinsing the bowl came immediately before. The shower and oatmeal came earlier."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Interpret Events in a Sequence","difficulty":2,"type":"ORDERED","stem":"Read the directions for brewing tea, then arrange the steps in the correct order from first to last.\n\nTo brew a proper cup of loose-leaf tea, begin by heating fresh water until it just reaches a boil. Pour the hot water over the leaves resting in the strainer. Allow the tea to steep for four minutes. Once the time is up, lift out the strainer and discard the spent leaves.","options":["Let the tea steep for four minutes.","Lift out the strainer and discard the leaves.","Pour the hot water over the leaves in the strainer.","Heat fresh water until it just boils."],"correct":[3,2,0,1],"explanation":"The directions give the order: heat water, pour over leaves, steep four minutes, then remove the strainer and discard the leaves."},
  {"section":"READING","topic":"key-ideas-details","subtopic":"Interpret Events in a Sequence","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the passage and answer the question.\n\nThe historical marker summarized the mill's life in a few lines. Founded in 1840, the textile mill prospered until a fire gutted it in 1871. Rebuilt within two years, it ran steadily until the river was dammed upstream in 1908, cutting its water power. The mill closed for good in 1915 and was converted into apartments in 1990.\n\nAccording to the passage, which event happened directly after the mill was rebuilt?","options":["The mill was converted into apartments.","The mill was founded.","The river was dammed upstream, cutting the mill's water power.","A fire gutted the mill."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The mill was rebuilt by 1873 and ran steadily until the 1908 dam cut its water power, the next event in the sequence. The fire and founding came before the rebuild, and the apartment conversion came much later."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Interpret Relevant Information from Tables, Charts, and Graphs","difficulty":1,"stem":"The table shows the number of pizzas sold at a cafe each day. Day | Pizzas: Monday | 18, Tuesday | 24, Wednesday | 15, Thursday | 30, Friday | 27. How many more pizzas were sold on Thursday than on Wednesday?","options":["30","12","15","45"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Find the difference between Thursday and Wednesday: 30 - 15 = 15 pizzas. The trap 45 adds the two values, and 30 simply reads Thursday's total without comparing."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Interpret Relevant Information from Tables, Charts, and Graphs","difficulty":2,"stem":"The table shows points scored by four players in a trivia game. Player | Points: Ava | 32, Ben | 27, Cara | 41, Dan | 19. Together, how many points did the four players score?","options":["121","119","109","100"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Add all four totals: 32 + 27 + 41 + 19. Step by step: 32 + 27 = 59, 59 + 41 = 100, 100 + 19 = 119 points."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Interpret Relevant Information from Tables, Charts, and Graphs","difficulty":2,"stem":"A line graph shows a seedling's height measured each week. Week 1: 3 cm, Week 2: 5 cm, Week 3: 8 cm, Week 4: 8 cm, Week 5: 12 cm. Between which two consecutive weeks did the height NOT change?","options":["Week 2 and Week 3","Week 1 and Week 2","Week 4 and Week 5","Week 3 and Week 4"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The height stays the same only where two consecutive readings are equal. Week 3 is 8 cm and Week 4 is 8 cm, so there is no change between them. Every other consecutive pair increases."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Evaluate Information in Tables, Charts, and Graphs Using Statistics","difficulty":1,"stem":"A nurse records the resting heart rates (in beats per minute) of five patients: 68, 72, 80, 75, 65. What is the mean heart rate?","options":["80","73","75","72"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The mean is the sum divided by the count. Sum: 68 + 72 + 80 + 75 + 65 = 360. Divide by 5: 360 / 5 = 72 beats per minute. The value 75 is the median, not the mean."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Evaluate Information in Tables, Charts, and Graphs Using Statistics","difficulty":2,"stem":"The ages of six people in a study are: 22, 31, 19, 45, 28, 37. What is the median age?","options":["30","31","28","29.5"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Order the values: 19, 22, 28, 31, 37, 45. With an even count of six, the median is the average of the two middle values (28 and 31): (28 + 31) / 2 = 29.5."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Evaluate Information in Tables, Charts, and Graphs Using Statistics","difficulty":2,"type":"FILL_BLANK","stem":"A data set of daily rainfall amounts (in mm) is: 7, 12, 4, 19, 10. What is the range of the data set? Enter your answer in mm.","options":[],"correct":["15","15 mm","15mm"],"explanation":"The range is the largest value minus the smallest value. The maximum is 19 and the minimum is 4, so the range is 19 - 4 = 15 mm."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Explain the Relationship Between Variables","difficulty":2,"stem":"A car travels at a constant speed. The table shows distance over time. Time (hours) | Distance (miles): 1 | 55, 2 | 110, 3 | 165, 4 | 220. Based on the table, how many miles does the car travel each hour?","options":["55 miles","165 miles","110 miles","50 miles"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The distance increases by the same amount for each additional hour: 110 - 55 = 55, 165 - 110 = 55, 220 - 165 = 55. The car travels 55 miles per hour."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Explain the Relationship Between Variables","difficulty":1,"stem":"A study records the relationship between hours studied and test score. As the number of hours studied increases, the test score also increases. What kind of relationship does this describe between the two variables?","options":["An inverse relationship","A negative relationship","A positive relationship","No relationship"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"When one variable increases as the other increases, the two variables move in the same direction, which is a positive relationship. A negative or inverse relationship would have one increasing while the other decreases."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Explain the Relationship Between Variables","difficulty":3,"stem":"A worker is paid a fixed amount per item assembled. The table shows total pay for items assembled. Items | Pay: 5 | $40, 10 | $80, 15 | $120. At this rate, how much would the worker earn for assembling 25 items?","options":["$240","$180","$200","$160"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Find the rate per item: $40 / 5 = $8 per item (confirmed by $80 / 10 = $8). For 25 items: 25 x $8 = $200."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":1,"stem":"A rectangular garden measures 12 meters long and 7 meters wide. What is the area of the garden?","options":["38 m²","84 m","19 m²","84 m²"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Area of a rectangle is length times width: 12 x 7 = 84 m². The value 38 is the perimeter (2 x (12 + 7)), and area must use square units, not 84 m."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":2,"stem":"A circular tabletop has a diameter of 10 inches. Using π ≈ 3.14, what is the area of the tabletop? (Area = π × radius²)","options":["31.4 in²","78.5 in²","314 in²","157 in²"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The radius is half the diameter: 10 / 2 = 5 inches. Area = 3.14 x 5² = 3.14 x 25 = 78.5 in². The trap 314 comes from using the diameter (10) as the radius."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Calculate Geometric Quantities","difficulty":2,"stem":"A rectangular storage box is 4 cm long, 3 cm wide, and 5 cm tall. What is the volume of the box?","options":["12 cm³","47 cm³","60 cm³","60 cm²"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Volume of a rectangular prism is length times width times height: 4 x 3 x 5 = 60 cm³. Volume uses cubic units, so 60 cm² is incorrectly labeled."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Convert Within and Between Standard and Metric Units","difficulty":1,"stem":"A bandage is 6 inches long. Using 1 inch = 2.54 cm, what is its length in centimeters?","options":["8.54 cm","15.24 in","15.24 cm","2.36 cm"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Multiply inches by 2.54 to get centimeters: 6 x 2.54 = 15.24 cm. The value 2.36 comes from dividing (wrong direction), and the answer must be in cm, not inches."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Convert Within and Between Standard and Metric Units","difficulty":2,"stem":"A patient weighs 70 kilograms. Using 1 kg ≈ 2.2 lb, approximately what is the patient's weight in pounds?","options":["72.2 lb","140 lb","154 lb","31.8 lb"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Multiply kilograms by 2.2 to get pounds: 70 x 2.2 = 154 lb. The trap 31.8 comes from dividing 70 by 2.2 (converting the wrong direction)."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"measurement-data","subtopic":"Convert Within and Between Standard and Metric Units","difficulty":2,"type":"FILL_BLANK","stem":"A container holds 2.5 liters of solution. Using 1 L = 1000 mL, how many milliliters does it hold? Enter your answer in mL.","options":[],"correct":["2500","2500 mL","2500mL"],"explanation":"Multiply liters by 1000 to get milliliters: 2.5 x 1000 = 2500 mL."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":2,"stem":"What is 3/8 + 5/6?","options":["1 5/24","8/14","1 1/24","29/48"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The least common denominator of 8 and 6 is 24. Rewrite: 3/8 = 9/24 and 5/6 = 20/24. Then 9/24 + 20/24 = 29/24 = 1 5/24. The choice 8/14 comes from adding numerators and denominators; 29/48 from multiplying the denominators instead of using the LCD."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":1,"stem":"What is 4.7 − 1.85?","options":["2.85","2.95","2.65","3.85"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Align the decimals: 4.70 − 1.85. Subtracting gives 2.85. The choice 3.85 ignores the borrow in the tenths place, and 2.95 mishandles the hundredths borrow."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Perform Arithmetic Operations with Rational Numbers (Whole Numbers, Decimals, & Fractions)","difficulty":2,"stem":"What is 2/3 × 9/14 in simplest form?","options":["9/21","11/17","18/42","3/7"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Multiply numerators and denominators: (2 × 9)/(3 × 14) = 18/42. Divide numerator and denominator by 6 to get 3/7. The choice 11/17 comes from adding across, and 18/42 is the correct product left unsimplified."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Convert Among Decimals, Fractions & Percents","difficulty":2,"stem":"Write 0.625 as a fraction in simplest form.","options":["5/8","1/16","5/16","3/5"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"0.625 = 625/1000. Dividing numerator and denominator by 125 gives 5/8. The choice 3/5 reads the digits loosely, and 5/16 over-reduces incorrectly."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Convert Among Decimals, Fractions & Percents","difficulty":1,"stem":"Convert 7/20 to a percent.","options":["7.2%","27%","35%","0.35%"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"7/20 = 0.35, and 0.35 = 35%. The choice 0.35% forgets to multiply the decimal by 100, and 7.2% misreads the fraction."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Convert Among Decimals, Fractions & Percents","difficulty":2,"type":"FILL_BLANK","stem":"Express 0.4% as a decimal.","options":[],"correct":["0.004",".004"],"explanation":"To convert a percent to a decimal, divide by 100 (move the decimal point two places left): 0.4% = 0.4 ÷ 100 = 0.004."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Solve Real World Problems Involving Percents","difficulty":2,"stem":"A jacket priced at $80 is marked down 35%. What is the sale price?","options":["$52","$45","$115","$28"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The discount is 80 × 0.35 = $28. The sale price is 80 − 28 = $52. The choice $28 is the discount amount, not the price, and $45 uses 45% off by mistake."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Solve Real World Problems Involving Percents","difficulty":2,"stem":"18 is what percent of 45?","options":["2.5%","25%","40%","27%"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Divide the part by the whole: 18 ÷ 45 = 0.4 = 40%. The choice 2.5% inverts the division (45 ÷ 18), and 25% guesses without computing."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Solve Real World Problems Involving Percents","difficulty":3,"stem":"A town's population grows from 250 to 320 people. What is the percent increase?","options":["21.875%","22%","28%","70%"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The increase is 320 − 250 = 70. Divide by the original amount: 70 ÷ 250 = 0.28 = 28%. The choice 21.875% divides by the new amount (320) instead of the original, and 70% mistakes the raw change for the percent."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Compare & Order Rational Numbers","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which of the following numbers is the greatest: 0.6, 5/8, 0.58, or 3/5?","options":["0.58","3/5","5/8","0.6"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Convert to decimals: 5/8 = 0.625, 3/5 = 0.6, plus 0.6 and 0.58. The largest value is 0.625, which is 5/8."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Compare & Order Rational Numbers","difficulty":3,"stem":"Order from least to greatest: −2/3, −0.7, −5/8.","options":["−5/8, −2/3, −0.7","−2/3, −0.7, −5/8","−0.7, −5/8, −2/3","−0.7, −2/3, −5/8"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"As decimals: −2/3 ≈ −0.667, −0.7 = −0.7, −5/8 = −0.625. For negatives, the more negative value is smaller, so −0.7 < −0.667 < −0.625. The order is −0.7, −2/3, −5/8."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Compare & Order Rational Numbers","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which value lies between 1/4 and 1/2?","options":["1/3","1/5","3/5","1/8"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"As decimals, 1/4 = 0.25 and 1/2 = 0.5. Only 1/3 ≈ 0.333 falls between them. The choices 1/5 = 0.2 and 1/8 = 0.125 are below 0.25, and 3/5 = 0.6 is above 0.5."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Solve Equations in One Variable","difficulty":1,"stem":"Solve for x: 5x − 7 = 28.","options":["7","4.2","35","5"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Add 7 to both sides: 5x = 35. Divide by 5: x = 7. The choice 4.2 comes from dividing 28 by 5 before adding 7, and 35 stops at 5x = 35 without dividing."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Solve Equations in One Variable","difficulty":2,"stem":"Solve for x: 3(x + 4) = 2x + 19.","options":["31","7","1.4","−7"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Distribute: 3x + 12 = 2x + 19. Subtract 2x: x + 12 = 19. Subtract 12: x = 7. The choice −7 has a sign error, and 31 forgets to combine the x terms."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Solve Equations in One Variable","difficulty":2,"type":"FILL_BLANK","stem":"Solve for x: x/4 + 6 = 14.","options":[],"correct":["32"],"explanation":"Subtract 6 from both sides: x/4 = 8. Multiply both sides by 4: x = 32."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Apply Estimation Strategies and Rounding Rules to Real World Problems","difficulty":1,"stem":"Estimate the product 48 × 21 by first rounding each factor to the nearest ten.","options":["1,000","1,050","980","900"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Round 48 to 50 and 21 to 20, then multiply: 50 × 20 = 1,000. The choice 980 is the exact product, not the estimate, and 900 rounds 48 down to 40 incorrectly."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Apply Estimation Strategies and Rounding Rules to Real World Problems","difficulty":2,"stem":"A shopper buys items costing $12.89, $7.45, and $4.99. Estimate the total by rounding each price to the nearest dollar.","options":["$26","$25","$24","$23"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Round to $13, $7, and $5. Adding gives 13 + 7 + 5 = $25. The choice $24 rounds $7.45 down to $7 but also $12.89 down to $12, and $23 rounds everything down."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Apply Estimation Strategies and Rounding Rules to Real World Problems","difficulty":1,"stem":"Round 7.3856 to the nearest hundredth.","options":["7.38","7.40","7.39","7.386"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The hundredths digit is 8, and the next digit (thousandths) is 5, so round up: 7.39. The choice 7.38 fails to round up, and 7.386 rounds to the thousandth instead."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Solve Real World Problems Involving Proportions, Ratios, and Rates of Change","difficulty":1,"stem":"A car travels 180 miles in 3 hours at a constant speed. What is its average speed?","options":["540 mph","63 mph","60 mph","54 mph"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Average speed is distance divided by time: 180 ÷ 3 = 60 mph. The choice 540 mph multiplies instead of divides, and 54 mph subtracts incorrectly."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Solve Real World Problems Involving Proportions, Ratios, and Rates of Change","difficulty":2,"type":"FILL_BLANK","stem":"A recipe uses flour and sugar in a ratio of 3 cups flour to 2 cups sugar. If 12 cups of flour are used, how many cups of sugar are needed?","options":[],"correct":["8","8 cups"],"explanation":"Set up the proportion 3/2 = 12/x. Cross multiply: 3x = 24, so x = 8 cups of sugar. (The flour was scaled up by a factor of 4, so 2 × 4 = 8.)"},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Solve Real World Problems Involving Proportions, Ratios, and Rates of Change","difficulty":2,"stem":"If 5 pens cost $6.25, how much do 8 pens cost at the same unit price?","options":["$10.50","$10.00","$8.00","$12.50"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The unit price is 6.25 ÷ 5 = $1.25 per pen. For 8 pens: 1.25 × 8 = $10.00. The choice $12.50 doubles the original price, and $8.00 ignores the unit cost."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Translate Phrases and Sentences into Expressions, Equations, and Inequalities","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which expression represents 'five less than three times a number n'?","options":["5 − 3n","3n − 5","5n − 3","3(n − 5)"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"'Three times a number' is 3n, and 'five less than' that means subtract 5: 3n − 5. The choice 5 − 3n reverses the subtraction order, and 3(n − 5) groups incorrectly."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Translate Phrases and Sentences into Expressions, Equations, and Inequalities","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which inequality represents 'the sum of a number x and 8 is at least 20'?","options":["8 − x ≥ 20","x + 8 ≥ 20","x + 8 > 20","x + 8 ≤ 20"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"'The sum of x and 8' is x + 8, and 'at least 20' means 20 or more, written ≥ 20. The choice x + 8 > 20 excludes 20, and ≤ reverses the direction."},
  {"section":"MATH","topic":"numbers-algebra","subtopic":"Translate Phrases and Sentences into Expressions, Equations, and Inequalities","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which expression represents 'twice the difference of a number x and 7'?","options":["2(7 − x)","2x + 7","2x − 7","2(x − 7)"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"'The difference of x and 7' is (x − 7), and 'twice' that quantity means multiply the whole difference by 2: 2(x − 7). The choice 2x − 7 only doubles x, and 2(7 − x) reverses the difference."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Demonstrate Knowledge of the General Orientation of Human Anatomy","difficulty":1,"stem":"A clinician notes that the wrist is located distal to the elbow. Which relationship does the term distal describe?","options":["Nearer to the front of the body","Toward the midline of the body","Closer to the point of limb attachment","Farther from the trunk along a limb"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Distal means farther from the point of attachment of a limb to the trunk, so the wrist is distal to the elbow. Proximal is closer to the attachment, anterior is toward the front, and medial is toward the midline."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Demonstrate Knowledge of the General Orientation of Human Anatomy","difficulty":2,"stem":"A plane that divides the body into superior and inferior portions is referred to as which plane?","options":["Transverse plane","Midsagittal plane","Frontal plane","Sagittal plane"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The transverse (horizontal) plane separates the body into superior (upper) and inferior (lower) portions. Sagittal planes divide left from right, and the frontal (coronal) plane divides anterior from posterior."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Demonstrate Knowledge of the General Orientation of Human Anatomy","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which body cavity is bounded inferiorly by the diaphragm and contains the heart and lungs?","options":["Pelvic cavity","Abdominal cavity","Cranial cavity","Thoracic cavity"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The thoracic cavity lies above the diaphragm and houses the heart and lungs. The abdominal and pelvic cavities lie below the diaphragm, and the cranial cavity holds the brain."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Respiratory System","difficulty":2,"stem":"Gas exchange between inhaled air and the blood occurs across the walls of which structures?","options":["Alveoli","Trachea","Pleurae","Bronchioles"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Oxygen and carbon dioxide diffuse across the thin walls of the alveoli, which are surrounded by pulmonary capillaries. Bronchioles and the trachea conduct air but do not exchange gas, and the pleurae are membranes around the lungs."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Respiratory System","difficulty":2,"stem":"When the diaphragm contracts and flattens during quiet breathing, what is the direct result inside the thoracic cavity?","options":["Intrapulmonary pressure rises above atmospheric pressure","Thoracic volume increases and air is drawn in","Thoracic volume decreases and air is pushed out","The lungs recoil passively to expel air"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Contraction of the diaphragm increases the volume of the thoracic cavity, lowering intrapulmonary pressure below atmospheric pressure so air flows in (inspiration). Decreasing volume and passive recoil describe expiration."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Respiratory System","difficulty":3,"stem":"Most carbon dioxide is transported in the blood from the tissues to the lungs in which chemical form?","options":["As bicarbonate ions in the plasma","As carbonic acid stored in red blood cell nuclei","Dissolved as free carbon dioxide gas in plasma","Bound to the heme groups of hemoglobin"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"About 70 percent of carbon dioxide is carried as bicarbonate ions formed when carbon dioxide reacts with water. A smaller amount binds to the globin portion of hemoglobin as carbaminohemoglobin, and only a small fraction is dissolved. Mature red blood cells have no nucleus."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Cardiovascular System","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which chamber of the heart pumps oxygenated blood into the aorta for distribution to the body?","options":["Left ventricle","Right atrium","Left atrium","Right ventricle"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The left ventricle pumps oxygenated blood into the aorta and out to the systemic circulation. The right ventricle sends blood to the lungs, while the atria are receiving chambers."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Cardiovascular System","difficulty":2,"stem":"The electrical impulse that normally initiates each heartbeat originates in which structure?","options":["Bundle of His","Atrioventricular node","Sinoatrial node","Purkinje fibers"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The sinoatrial node in the right atrium is the heart's natural pacemaker and sets the rhythm. The atrioventricular node, bundle of His, and Purkinje fibers conduct the impulse onward but do not normally initiate it."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Cardiovascular System","difficulty":3,"stem":"The atrioventricular (AV) valve located between the left atrium and left ventricle is the:","options":["Pulmonary semilunar valve","Tricuspid valve","Bicuspid (mitral) valve","Aortic semilunar valve"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The bicuspid, or mitral, valve sits between the left atrium and left ventricle. The tricuspid valve is on the right side, and the semilunar valves guard the exits to the pulmonary artery and aorta."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Gastrointestinal System","difficulty":2,"stem":"Most absorption of nutrients into the bloodstream occurs in which segment of the digestive tract?","options":["Large intestine","Stomach","Small intestine","Esophagus"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The small intestine, with its villi and microvilli, is the primary site of nutrient absorption. The stomach mainly mixes and digests food, the large intestine absorbs water and electrolytes, and the esophagus only transports food."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Gastrointestinal System","difficulty":2,"stem":"Bile, which emulsifies dietary fats, is produced by which organ?","options":["Spleen","Pancreas","Liver","Gallbladder"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The liver produces bile, which is then concentrated and stored in the gallbladder before release into the small intestine. The pancreas secretes digestive enzymes and bicarbonate, and the spleen is not a digestive organ."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Gastrointestinal System","difficulty":3,"stem":"The enzyme pepsin, which begins protein digestion, requires which environment to function effectively?","options":["The fat-rich environment of the gallbladder","The alkaline environment of the small intestine","The acidic environment of the stomach","The neutral pH of saliva in the mouth"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Pepsin is activated from pepsinogen by hydrochloric acid and works best in the strongly acidic environment of the stomach. The small intestine is alkaline, where pancreatic proteases continue protein digestion."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Neuromuscular System","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which neurotransmitter is released at the neuromuscular junction to stimulate contraction of skeletal muscle?","options":["Acetylcholine","Serotonin","Gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA)","Dopamine"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Motor neurons release acetylcholine at the neuromuscular junction, which binds receptors on the muscle fiber and triggers contraction. Dopamine, serotonin, and GABA act within the central nervous system, not at the skeletal neuromuscular junction."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Neuromuscular System","difficulty":3,"stem":"During skeletal muscle contraction, the release of which ion from the sarcoplasmic reticulum exposes the binding sites needed for the cross-bridge cycle?","options":["Calcium","Sodium","Potassium","Chloride"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Calcium ions released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum bind troponin, shifting tropomyosin off the actin binding sites so myosin cross-bridges can form. Sodium and potassium drive the action potential, but calcium directly triggers the contraction."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Neuromuscular System","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which type of muscle tissue is under voluntary control and attaches to bones to produce movement?","options":["Cardiac muscle","Skeletal muscle","Visceral muscle","Smooth muscle"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Skeletal muscle is voluntary and striated and attaches to bones to move the skeleton. Cardiac muscle (heart) and smooth muscle (walls of hollow organs) are involuntary."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Reproductive System","difficulty":2,"stem":"In the male reproductive system, sperm cells are produced within which structures?","options":["Epididymis","Seminiferous tubules of the testes","Seminal vesicles","Prostate gland"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Spermatogenesis occurs in the seminiferous tubules of the testes. The epididymis stores and matures sperm, while the prostate and seminal vesicles add fluids to form semen."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Reproductive System","difficulty":2,"stem":"Following ovulation, fertilization of a secondary oocyte by a sperm cell normally occurs in which structure?","options":["Cervix","Uterine (fallopian) tube","Ovary","Uterus"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Fertilization typically takes place in the ampulla of the uterine (fallopian) tube. The fertilized egg then travels to the uterus to implant; the ovary releases the oocyte and the cervix is the lower uterine opening."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Reproductive System","difficulty":3,"stem":"A surge in which hormone directly triggers ovulation in the menstrual cycle?","options":["Follicle-stimulating hormone","Oxytocin","Luteinizing hormone","Progesterone"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"A sharp surge in luteinizing hormone from the anterior pituitary triggers ovulation near the middle of the cycle. Follicle-stimulating hormone promotes follicle growth earlier, and progesterone dominates the luteal phase after ovulation."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Integumentary System","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which layer of the epidermis contains actively dividing stem cells that continually replace the cells above it?","options":["Stratum basale","Stratum corneum","Stratum granulosum","Stratum lucidum"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The stratum basale (basal layer) is the deepest epidermal layer and houses keratinocyte stem cells that undergo mitosis to generate new cells, which then migrate upward. The stratum corneum is the outermost layer of dead, flattened cells, while the granulosum and lucidum are intermediate layers that do not perform the bulk of cell division."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Integumentary System","difficulty":2,"stem":"Exposure of the skin to ultraviolet radiation triggers the initial synthesis of which vitamin?","options":["Vitamin C","Vitamin D","Vitamin A","Vitamin K"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Ultraviolet light converts a cholesterol derivative in the skin into a precursor of vitamin D, which is later modified by the liver and kidneys into its active form. Vitamins A, C, and K are obtained through dietary intake and are not produced by UV exposure to the skin."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Integumentary System","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which type of sweat gland is distributed over most of the body surface and is most directly responsible for cooling the body through evaporation?","options":["Ceruminous glands","Apocrine glands","Eccrine glands","Sebaceous glands"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Eccrine glands are widespread across the skin and secrete a watery sweat that evaporates to dissipate heat, making them the primary glands of thermoregulation. Apocrine glands are concentrated in the axillary and genital regions, sebaceous glands secrete oily sebum, and ceruminous glands produce earwax."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Endocrine System","difficulty":2,"stem":"Antidiuretic hormone (ADH) and oxytocin are stored and released by which structure?","options":["Thyroid gland","Anterior pituitary","Posterior pituitary","Adrenal cortex"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"ADH and oxytocin are produced by neurons of the hypothalamus and travel down axons to be stored in and released from the posterior pituitary. The anterior pituitary secretes hormones such as growth hormone and ACTH, while the thyroid and adrenal cortex produce entirely different hormones."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Endocrine System","difficulty":2,"stem":"Calcitonin, a hormone that lowers blood calcium levels, is secreted by which gland?","options":["Pineal gland","Pancreas","Thyroid gland","Parathyroid gland"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The thyroid gland secretes calcitonin, which reduces blood calcium by inhibiting bone breakdown. This opposes parathyroid hormone from the parathyroid glands, which raises blood calcium. The pancreas regulates blood glucose, and the pineal gland secretes melatonin."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Endocrine System","difficulty":3,"stem":"During the fight-or-flight response, the adrenal medulla rapidly secretes which hormone to increase heart rate and mobilize energy?","options":["Aldosterone","Cortisol","Epinephrine","Thyroxine"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The adrenal medulla releases epinephrine (adrenaline), which raises heart rate, dilates airways, and increases blood glucose for rapid energy. Aldosterone and cortisol are produced by the adrenal cortex and act more slowly, while thyroxine from the thyroid governs baseline metabolic rate."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Genitourinary System","difficulty":1,"stem":"What is the functional filtering unit of the kidney?","options":["Alveolus","Nephron","Villus","Sarcomere"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The nephron is the microscopic functional unit of the kidney where blood is filtered and urine is formed. Alveoli are gas-exchange structures in the lungs, villi increase absorptive surface in the intestine, and sarcomeres are the contractile units of muscle."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Genitourinary System","difficulty":2,"stem":"In the nephron, the initial filtration of blood plasma occurs as fluid passes from the glomerulus into which structure?","options":["Collecting duct","Glomerular (Bowman) capsule","Loop of Henle","Renal pelvis"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Blood pressure forces plasma out of the glomerular capillaries into the surrounding glomerular (Bowman) capsule, forming the filtrate. The loop of Henle and collecting duct modify the filtrate later in the nephron, and the renal pelvis collects finished urine before it enters the ureter."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Genitourinary System","difficulty":2,"stem":"Antidiuretic hormone (ADH) helps conserve body water primarily by increasing water reabsorption in which part of the nephron?","options":["Glomerulus","Collecting duct","Renal corpuscle","Proximal convoluted tubule"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"ADH increases the permeability of the collecting duct to water, allowing more water to be reabsorbed into the blood and producing concentrated urine. The glomerulus performs filtration, and although the proximal tubule reabsorbs much fluid, it does so independently of ADH regulation."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Immune System","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which cells differentiate into plasma cells that secrete antibodies?","options":["Osteocytes","B lymphocytes","Red blood cells","Platelets"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"B lymphocytes (B cells) mature into plasma cells that produce and release antibodies targeting specific antigens. Red blood cells transport oxygen, platelets aid clotting, and osteocytes are bone cells, none of which produce antibodies."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Immune System","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which of the following is a feature of innate (nonspecific) immunity rather than adaptive immunity?","options":["Activation of specific helper T cells","Production of antigen-specific antibodies","Immunological memory of past infections","The skin acting as a physical barrier to pathogens"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The skin is a physical barrier that blocks pathogens without targeting any specific microbe, making it part of innate immunity. Antibody production, immunological memory, and helper T cell activation are all hallmarks of the adaptive immune response, which is specific to particular antigens."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Immune System","difficulty":3,"stem":"Cytotoxic T cells protect the body primarily by performing which action?","options":["Secreting large quantities of antibodies into the blood","Producing histamine during allergic reactions","Destroying body cells infected with viruses","Engulfing pathogens as the first responders of inflammation"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Cytotoxic (CD8) T cells recognize and kill the body's own cells that have become infected by viruses or turned cancerous. Antibody secretion is performed by plasma cells, histamine release is carried out by mast cells and basophils, and neutrophils and macrophages are the phagocytes of early inflammation."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Skeletal System","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which bone cells are responsible for breaking down bone matrix and releasing stored calcium into the blood?","options":["Chondrocytes","Osteoblasts","Osteocytes","Osteoclasts"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Osteoclasts are large cells that resorb bone tissue, releasing calcium and other minerals into the bloodstream. Osteoblasts build new bone, osteocytes are mature bone cells maintaining the matrix, and chondrocytes are found in cartilage rather than bone."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Skeletal System","difficulty":1,"stem":"Red bone marrow performs which important function?","options":["Synthesis of bile","Production of blood cells","Secretion of digestive enzymes","Storage of urine"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Red bone marrow is the site of hematopoiesis, the production of red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets. Digestive enzyme secretion occurs in the pancreas and intestine, urine is stored in the bladder, and bile is made by the liver."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"anatomy-physiology","subtopic":"Skeletal System","difficulty":2,"stem":"The joint at the elbow that allows flexion and extension in a single plane is best classified as which type of joint?","options":["Ball-and-socket joint","Pivot joint","Gliding joint","Hinge joint"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The elbow is a hinge joint, permitting movement in one plane like the opening and closing of a door. Ball-and-socket joints such as the hip allow movement in many directions, pivot joints permit rotation, and gliding joints allow bones to slide across one another."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Describe Cell Structure, Function, and Organization","difficulty":2,"stem":"A researcher examines a cell and finds it has no membrane-bound nucleus, a single circular chromosome, and a peptidoglycan cell wall. Into which category does this cell best fit?","options":["Eukaryotic fungal cell","Eukaryotic plant cell","Prokaryotic bacterial cell","Eukaryotic animal cell"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Lacking a true nucleus, carrying a single circular chromosome, and possessing a peptidoglycan wall are defining features of a prokaryotic bacterial cell. All listed eukaryotic cells have a membrane-bound nucleus and lack peptidoglycan."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Describe Cell Structure, Function, and Organization","difficulty":2,"stem":"A liver cell devotes many resources to detoxifying drugs and synthesizing lipids. Which organelle would be especially abundant to support these specific functions?","options":["Smooth endoplasmic reticulum","Rough endoplasmic reticulum","Lysosome","Nucleolus"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The smooth endoplasmic reticulum handles lipid synthesis and the detoxification of drugs and poisons. The rough ER is studded with ribosomes for protein synthesis, the nucleolus makes ribosome subunits, and lysosomes carry out intracellular digestion."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Describe Cell Structure, Function, and Organization","difficulty":1,"stem":"In the levels of biological organization, which sequence is arranged correctly from smallest to largest?","options":["Cell, organ, tissue, organ system","Organ, organ system, tissue, cell","Cell, tissue, organ, organ system","Tissue, cell, organ system, organ"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Organization builds from cells to tissues (groups of similar cells), then organs (groups of tissues), then organ systems (groups of organs working together). Only the first option lists this order correctly."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Describe the Relationship Between Genetic Material and Protein Structure","difficulty":2,"stem":"During transcription, a segment of DNA template reads 3'-TACGGT-5'. What is the corresponding sequence of the messenger RNA produced?","options":["5'-UACGGU-3'","5'-AUGCCA-3'","5'-TACGGT-3'","5'-ATGCCA-3'"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"RNA is built by complementary base pairing with the DNA template, using uracil in place of thymine. Pairing each template base (T-A, A-U, C-G, G-C, G-C, T-A) gives 5'-AUGCCA-3'. Options with thymine are incorrect because RNA never contains thymine."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Describe the Relationship Between Genetic Material and Protein Structure","difficulty":3,"stem":"A point mutation changes a single DNA base, yet the resulting protein has the exact same amino acid sequence as before. Which term best describes this type of mutation?","options":["Silent mutation","Nonsense mutation","Frameshift mutation","Missense mutation"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Because the genetic code is redundant, several codons can specify the same amino acid. A base change that still codes for the same amino acid is a silent mutation. A nonsense mutation creates a stop codon, a missense mutation swaps in a different amino acid, and a frameshift results from insertions or deletions."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Describe the Relationship Between Genetic Material and Protein Structure","difficulty":1,"stem":"In a eukaryotic cell, in which location does translation, the assembly of a polypeptide from a messenger RNA template, take place?","options":["Golgi apparatus","Nucleus","Nucleolus","Ribosome"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Translation occurs at the ribosome, where transfer RNA delivers amino acids to match the messenger RNA codons. Transcription occurs in the nucleus, the nucleolus assembles ribosome subunits, and the Golgi apparatus modifies and packages finished proteins."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Apply Concepts Underlying Mendel's Laws of Inheritance","difficulty":2,"stem":"In pea plants, purple flower color (P) is dominant to white (p). Two heterozygous purple-flowered plants (Pp) are crossed. What fraction of the offspring is expected to have white flowers?","options":["0","3/4","1/2","1/4"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"A Pp x Pp cross yields genotypes in a 1 PP : 2 Pp : 1 pp ratio. Only the pp genotype produces white flowers, so 1 out of 4 offspring, or 1/4, are expected to be white."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Apply Concepts Underlying Mendel's Laws of Inheritance","difficulty":3,"stem":"In a certain plant, tall (T) is dominant to short (t). A test cross is performed between a tall plant of unknown genotype and a short plant (tt), producing 50% tall and 50% short offspring. What is the genotype of the tall parent?","options":["tt","Tt","TTtt","TT"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"A test cross with a homozygous recessive (tt) reveals the unknown genotype. A Tt x tt cross gives 1 Tt : 1 tt, a 50% tall to 50% short ratio. If the tall parent were TT, all offspring would be tall, so the parent must be heterozygous Tt."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Apply Concepts Underlying Mendel's Laws of Inheritance","difficulty":2,"stem":"In snapdragons, flower color shows incomplete dominance: red (RR) crossed with white (rr) produces all pink (Rr) flowers. If two pink snapdragons are crossed, what phenotype ratio is expected in the offspring?","options":["3 pink : 1 white","1 red : 2 pink : 1 white","3 red : 1 white","All pink"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"With incomplete dominance, the heterozygote (Rr) shows the blended pink phenotype. An Rr x Rr cross gives a 1 RR : 2 Rr : 1 rr genotype ratio, which corresponds directly to 1 red : 2 pink : 1 white because each genotype has its own distinct phenotype."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Describe the Structure and Function of the Basic Macromolecules in a Biological System","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which monomer serves as the building block of proteins?","options":["Fatty acids","Amino acids","Nucleotides","Monosaccharides"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Proteins are polymers of amino acids joined by peptide bonds. Monosaccharides build carbohydrates, nucleotides build nucleic acids, and fatty acids are components of many lipids."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Describe the Structure and Function of the Basic Macromolecules in a Biological System","difficulty":2,"stem":"A nutrition label lists a food as rich in starch and glycogen-forming sugars used mainly for quick energy. To which class of macromolecules do starch and glycogen belong?","options":["Carbohydrates","Lipids","Proteins","Nucleic acids"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Starch and glycogen are polysaccharides, polymers of glucose, and therefore carbohydrates. They serve as energy-storage molecules. Proteins, lipids, and nucleic acids are built from different monomers and serve different primary roles."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Describe the Structure and Function of the Basic Macromolecules in a Biological System","difficulty":3,"type":"MULTI","stem":"A student is asked to identify properties that are characteristic of lipids. Which of the following statements about lipids are correct? Select all that apply.","options":["They are polymers built from amino acid monomers","They are the primary carriers of hereditary information","They are generally hydrophobic and do not dissolve well in water","They include fats, oils, and steroids"],"correct":[2,3],"explanation":"Lipids are largely nonpolar, making them hydrophobic, and the group includes fats, oils, and steroids. Lipids are not built from amino acids (that describes proteins), and they do not store hereditary information (that is the role of nucleic acids)."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Describe the Role of Microorganisms in Disease","difficulty":1,"stem":"A physician explains that a patient's illness is caused by a pathogen that can only reproduce after entering a host cell and hijacking its machinery. Which type of microorganism best fits this description?","options":["Fungus","Protozoan","Virus","Bacterium"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Viruses are obligate intracellular parasites; they cannot replicate on their own and must take over a host cell's machinery to make new viral particles. Bacteria, protozoa, and fungi are cellular organisms capable of reproducing independently."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Describe the Role of Microorganisms in Disease","difficulty":2,"stem":"A patient is prescribed an antibiotic for a confirmed bacterial infection. Why would this same medication be ineffective against the patient's later case of influenza?","options":["Influenza viruses are too large for antibiotics to penetrate","Antibiotics destroy human cells but spare viral particles","Influenza is caused by a virus, and antibiotics target structures and processes specific to bacteria","Antibiotics only work on fungal cell walls, not bacterial ones"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Antibiotics act on features unique to bacteria, such as their cell walls or bacterial ribosomes, so they have no effect on viruses like influenza, which lack these structures. Viral infections require antiviral drugs or the body's immune response instead."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"biology","subtopic":"Describe the Role of Microorganisms in Disease","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which of the following diseases is caused by a fungus rather than a bacterium or virus?","options":["Strep throat","Tuberculosis","Measles","Athlete's foot (tinea pedis)"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Athlete's foot is a fungal infection of the skin. Tuberculosis and strep throat are caused by bacteria, and measles is caused by a virus."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"chemistry","subtopic":"Recognize Basic Atomic Structure","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which subatomic particle carries a negative electric charge?","options":["Nucleus","Neutron","Proton","Electron"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Electrons carry a negative charge. Protons are positive, neutrons are neutral, and the nucleus is the central region containing protons and neutrons, not a single particle."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"chemistry","subtopic":"Recognize Basic Atomic Structure","difficulty":2,"stem":"A neutral atom has a mass number of 39 and an atomic number of 19. How many neutrons does it contain?","options":["20","58","39","19"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The number of neutrons equals the mass number minus the atomic number: 39 minus 19 equals 20. The atomic number 19 also gives the number of protons and, in a neutral atom, the number of electrons."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"chemistry","subtopic":"Recognize Basic Atomic Structure","difficulty":3,"stem":"Two atoms are isotopes of the same element. Which statement must be true about them?","options":["They have the same mass number but different numbers of electrons","They have different atomic numbers but the same mass number","They have the same number of neutrons but different numbers of protons","They have the same number of protons but different numbers of neutrons"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Isotopes of an element share the same atomic number (same number of protons) but differ in the number of neutrons, which gives them different mass numbers. The proton count defines the element, so it cannot change between isotopes.","rationale":{"takeaway":"Isotopes: same protons, different neutrons.","whyCorrect":"The proton count defines the element, so two atoms of the same element must match there. The only thing free to differ is the neutron count, which is why isotopes have different mass numbers.","distractors":{"0":"Isotopes differ in mass number, and electron count is about charge (ions), not isotope identity.","1":"A different atomic number means a different proton count — and that would make them different elements, not isotopes.","2":"This is the definition backwards: it is the protons that must match and the neutrons that differ."},"commonMistake":"Swapping which particle stays fixed. Anchor on the rule that protons ARE the element's identity; everything else follows."}},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"chemistry","subtopic":"Explain Physical Properties and Changes of Matter","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which of the following is a physical change?","options":["Wood burning into ash and smoke","Iron rusting in moist air","Baking soda fizzing in vinegar","Ice melting into liquid water"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Melting ice changes only the physical state of water; no new substance forms. Burning, rusting, and the fizzing reaction between baking soda and vinegar all produce new chemical substances and are chemical changes."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"chemistry","subtopic":"Explain Physical Properties and Changes of Matter","difficulty":2,"stem":"Density is best classified as which type of property?","options":["A property that changes when a substance is cut in half","A chemical property observed only during a reaction","An intensive physical property that does not depend on sample size","An extensive physical property that depends on sample size"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Density is an intensive physical property: it is the same for a large or small sample of the same substance at a given temperature. Cutting the sample in half does not change its density, and no reaction is needed to measure it."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"chemistry","subtopic":"Explain Physical Properties and Changes of Matter","difficulty":2,"stem":"When solid carbon dioxide (dry ice) turns directly into a gas without first becoming a liquid, this phase change is called","options":["sublimation","vaporization","condensation","deposition"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Sublimation is the direct transition of a solid to a gas. Condensation is gas to liquid, vaporization is liquid to gas, and deposition is gas directly to solid. Sublimation is a physical change because the substance remains CO2."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"chemistry","subtopic":"Describe Chemical Reactions","difficulty":1,"stem":"In the reaction 2H2 + O2 → 2H2O, the substances on the left side of the arrow are called the","options":["products","reactants","solvents","catalysts"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Substances written to the left of the yields arrow are reactants, the starting materials. The substances formed on the right, here H2O, are the products. Catalysts speed reactions without being consumed, and solvents dissolve solutes."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"chemistry","subtopic":"Describe Chemical Reactions","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which coefficient should replace the blank to balance the equation N2 + ___ H2 → 2NH3?","options":["1","6","3","2"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The products contain 6 hydrogen atoms (2 times NH3). To supply 6 hydrogen atoms, 3 molecules of H2 are needed, giving 3 times 2 equals 6. A coefficient of 3 balances both nitrogen and hydrogen."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"chemistry","subtopic":"Describe Chemical Reactions","difficulty":3,"stem":"The reaction 2KClO3 → 2KCl + 3O2 is best classified as which type of reaction?","options":["Combustion","Single replacement","Decomposition","Synthesis"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"A single compound (KClO3) breaks apart into two simpler substances, which is a decomposition reaction. Synthesis combines substances into one product, single replacement swaps one element for another, and combustion requires reaction with oxygen to release energy."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"chemistry","subtopic":"Understand Properties of Solutions","difficulty":1,"stem":"When table salt is dissolved in water to make a saltwater solution, the water is acting as the","options":["solvent","precipitate","solute","product"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The solvent is the substance present in the greater amount that dissolves the solute. In saltwater, water is the solvent and salt is the solute. A precipitate is an insoluble solid that forms from a reaction."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"chemistry","subtopic":"Understand Properties of Solutions","difficulty":2,"stem":"A solution has a pH of 3. Which statement best describes this solution?","options":["It is basic and has a high concentration of hydroxide ions","It is acidic and has a high concentration of hydrogen ions","It is basic and has a low concentration of hydrogen ions","It is neutral with equal hydrogen and hydroxide ions"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"A pH below 7 is acidic, and the lower the pH, the higher the concentration of hydrogen ions. A pH of 3 indicates a strongly acidic solution. Neutral is pH 7 and basic solutions have a pH above 7."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"chemistry","subtopic":"Understand Properties of Solutions","difficulty":3,"stem":"Raising the temperature of water generally increases how much of a solid such as sugar will dissolve. This best illustrates that temperature can affect a solution's","options":["pH value","freezing point only","boiling point only","solubility"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Solubility is the maximum amount of solute that dissolves in a given amount of solvent under specific conditions. For most solids, higher temperature increases solubility. The change in dissolved amount reflects solubility, not the solution's pH or its phase change points."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"scientific-reasoning","subtopic":"Use Basic Scientific Measurements and Measurement Tools","difficulty":1,"stem":"A technician needs to measure the mass of a small amount of powdered salt for a chemistry experiment. The expected mass is about 2 grams. Which tool and unit pairing is most appropriate for this measurement?","options":["A meter stick reading in centimeters","A thermometer reading in degrees Celsius","An analytical balance reading in grams","A graduated cylinder reading in milliliters"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Mass is measured with a balance, and grams are the appropriate unit for a 2 g sample. A graduated cylinder measures volume, a thermometer measures temperature, and a meter stick measures length, so none of those match mass."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"scientific-reasoning","subtopic":"Use Basic Scientific Measurements and Measurement Tools","difficulty":2,"stem":"A student pours water into a graduated cylinder and records the volume four times, getting 24.8 mL, 24.9 mL, 24.8 mL, and 24.9 mL. The true volume is known to be 30.0 mL. Which statement best describes these measurements?","options":["They are precise but not accurate","They are both accurate and precise","They are accurate but not precise","They are neither accurate nor precise"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The readings cluster tightly together (within 0.1 mL), so they are precise. However, they all fall far from the true value of 30.0 mL, so they are not accurate. Precision refers to repeatability, while accuracy refers to closeness to the true value."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"scientific-reasoning","subtopic":"Use Basic Scientific Measurements and Measurement Tools","difficulty":2,"stem":"A nurse must give a patient a liquid medication dose of 0.5 grams. The medication bottle lists its concentration in milligrams per milliliter. To select the correct volume to draw into the syringe, what conversion must the nurse first apply to the ordered dose?","options":["Convert 0.5 grams to 500 milligrams","Convert 0.5 grams to 50 milligrams","Convert 0.5 grams to 5,000 milligrams","Convert 0.5 grams to 0.005 milligrams"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"There are 1,000 milligrams in 1 gram, so 0.5 grams equals 0.5 times 1,000, which is 500 milligrams. Matching the dose unit to the concentration unit (mg) is required before calculating the volume in milliliters."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"scientific-reasoning","subtopic":"Apply Logic and Evidence to Scientific Explanations","difficulty":2,"stem":"Researchers observed that towns with more ice cream sales also reported more cases of sunburn during the same months. A reporter concluded that eating ice cream causes sunburn. Which statement best explains the flaw in this conclusion?","options":["The study proves that sunburn causes people to buy ice cream","Ice cream sales were measured in the wrong units","Both variables likely rise together because of a third factor, hot sunny weather","The sample of towns was too large to draw any conclusion"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"A correlation between two variables does not establish causation. Both ice cream sales and sunburn cases increase in hot, sunny weather, which is a shared underlying cause. The reporter mistook this correlation for a direct causal link."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"scientific-reasoning","subtopic":"Apply Logic and Evidence to Scientific Explanations","difficulty":3,"stem":"A scientist proposes that a new fertilizer increases tomato yield. In a trial, 50 plants given the fertilizer averaged 4.2 kg of fruit, while 50 untreated plants averaged 4.1 kg. The difference was within the normal range of plant-to-plant variation. Which conclusion is best supported by this evidence?","options":["The fertilizer clearly doubles tomato yield","The data do not provide strong support that the fertilizer increases yield","The fertilizer decreases tomato yield in all conditions","The fertilizer is proven safe for human consumption"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"A 0.1 kg difference that falls within normal plant-to-plant variation is not strong evidence of an effect. The data neither clearly support nor reject a yield increase, so the most defensible conclusion is that support is weak. The other options overreach beyond what the evidence shows."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"scientific-reasoning","subtopic":"Apply Logic and Evidence to Scientific Explanations","difficulty":1,"stem":"A student claims that a plant grew taller because she spoke kind words to it daily. She also watered it more than the other plants during the same period. Why does this observation fail to support her claim about speaking to the plant?","options":["Two variables changed at once, so the cause of the growth cannot be isolated","The student measured height instead of mass","Plants are known to grow only in darkness","Speaking to plants is impossible to do daily"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Because the student changed both the speaking and the watering at the same time, the extra growth could be due to either factor. A valid test must change only one variable at a time so the cause can be identified."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"scientific-reasoning","subtopic":"Predict Relationships Among Events, Objects, and Processes","difficulty":2,"stem":"In a study of an enzyme, reaction rate increased steadily as temperature rose from 10 C to 37 C, then dropped sharply between 40 C and 50 C. Based on this pattern, what is the most reasonable prediction for the reaction rate at 60 C?","options":["The rate will continue increasing without limit","The rate will exactly equal the rate at 10 C","The rate will be very low because the enzyme is likely denatured","The rate will be higher than it was at 37 C"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The data show the rate falling sharply above 40 C, which indicates the enzyme is losing function at high temperatures. Extending this trend, at 60 C the enzyme would likely be denatured and the rate very low. The other options ignore the downward trend after 37 C."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"scientific-reasoning","subtopic":"Predict Relationships Among Events, Objects, and Processes","difficulty":2,"stem":"A spring is stretched and its length is measured under increasing loads: 0 g gives 10.0 cm, 100 g gives 12.0 cm, 200 g gives 14.0 cm, and 300 g gives 16.0 cm. If the pattern continues, what length is predicted at a load of 400 g?","options":["16.5 cm","14.0 cm","20.0 cm","18.0 cm"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Each additional 100 g stretches the spring by 2.0 cm in a consistent linear pattern. Continuing from 16.0 cm at 300 g, adding another 100 g adds 2.0 cm, giving 18.0 cm at 400 g."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"scientific-reasoning","subtopic":"Predict Relationships Among Events, Objects, and Processes","difficulty":3,"stem":"A population of bacteria doubles every 30 minutes under ideal conditions. A culture starts with 200 cells. Assuming ideal conditions continue, which prediction about the population after 90 minutes is correct?","options":["It will reach 1,600 cells","It will reach 600 cells","It will reach 2,000 cells","It will reach 800 cells"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"In 90 minutes there are three 30-minute doubling periods. Starting at 200, the count goes 200 to 400 to 800 to 1,600. Doubling is multiplicative, not additive, so 1,600 cells is the correct prediction."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"scientific-reasoning","subtopic":"Apply the Scientific Method to Interpret a Scientific Investigation","difficulty":1,"stem":"A researcher tests whether a plant food increases growth. She gives Group A plant food and gives Group B nothing, keeping light, water, soil, and pot size identical for both groups. What is the role of Group B in this experiment?","options":["It is the independent variable","It is the control group used for comparison","It is a confounding variable","It is the dependent variable"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Group B receives no plant food while all other conditions match Group A, making it the control group. The control provides a baseline to compare against so the effect of the plant food can be judged."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"scientific-reasoning","subtopic":"Apply the Scientific Method to Interpret a Scientific Investigation","difficulty":2,"stem":"An investigator studies how salt concentration affects how fast water boils. She prepares pots of water with 0 g, 5 g, 10 g, and 15 g of salt, using the same pot, stove setting, and starting water volume each time, and records the time to boil. What is the independent variable in this experiment?","options":["The stove setting used","The time it takes the water to boil","The volume of water in the pot","The amount of salt added to the water"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The independent variable is the factor the investigator deliberately changes, which is the amount of salt. The time to boil is the dependent variable being measured, while the stove setting and water volume are controlled constants."},
  {"section":"SCIENCE","topic":"scientific-reasoning","subtopic":"Apply the Scientific Method to Interpret a Scientific Investigation","difficulty":3,"stem":"A team tests a cold remedy. Volunteers who chose to take the remedy reported shorter colds than those who chose not to take it. A critic notes the result may be unreliable because participants selected their own group. Which change would most improve the validity of the investigation?","options":["Let participants report their symptoms less often","Randomly assign participants to the remedy or a placebo group","Increase the dose of the remedy for everyone","Remove the group that did not take the remedy"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Self-selection means the groups may differ in ways that affect cold length, such as overall health or behavior. Randomly assigning participants and using a placebo controls for these differences and isolates the remedy's effect. The other options do not address the self-selection bias."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Identifying Correct Spelling","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which word is spelled correctly?","options":["definitely","definatly","definitly","definately"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"\"Definitely\" is the correct spelling: define + the suffix spelled -itely, with no letter a. The other forms misplace or insert vowels."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Identifying Correct Spelling","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence contains no spelling errors?","options":["The librarian recommended a fascinating biography.","The librarian recommended a facinating biography.","The libarian recommended a fascinating biography.","The librarian recomended a fascinating biography."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Only the first sentence spells every word correctly. The others misspell \"librarian\" as \"libarian,\" \"recommended\" as \"recomended\" (one m), and \"fascinating\" as \"facinating\" (missing the silent c)."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Identifying Correct Spelling","difficulty":3,"stem":"Which word is spelled correctly?","options":["conscientous","consientious","consciencious","conscientious"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"\"Conscientious\" is correct, built on \"conscience\" with the ending -tious. The other options swap the c for an s, drop the i in -tious, or omit the first c."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Correct Use of End Punctuation","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["When does the new library open?","When does the new library open.","When does the new library open,","When does the new library open!"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"This is a direct question, so it must end with a question mark. A period, an exclamation point, and a comma are all incorrect end punctuation for a question."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Correct Use of End Punctuation","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["The shipment finally arrived on Tuesday afternoon.","The shipment finally arrived on Tuesday afternoon?","The shipment finally arrived on Tuesday afternoon","The shipment finally arrived on Tuesday afternoon!"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"This is a simple declarative statement, so it ends with a period. A question mark or exclamation point would mislabel its purpose, and omitting end punctuation entirely is incorrect."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Correct Use of End Punctuation","difficulty":3,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["The instructor asked whether everyone had finished the assignment.","The instructor asked whether everyone had finished the assignment?","The instructor asked, whether everyone had finished the assignment.","The instructor asked whether everyone had finished the assignment!"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"This sentence reports a question indirectly rather than asking one, so it ends with a period, not a question mark or exclamation point. No comma belongs after \"asked\" before the word \"whether.\""},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Using Commas with Introductory Words","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["Meanwhile, the technicians repaired the generator.","Meanwhile the technicians repaired the generator.","Meanwhile the technicians, repaired the generator.","Meanwhile, the technicians repaired, the generator."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"An introductory transitional word such as \"Meanwhile\" is set off by a comma. The other versions omit that comma or insert an extra comma between sentence parts that should not be separated."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Using Commas with Introductory Words","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["Because the storm intensified, officials canceled the parade.","Because the storm intensified officials canceled the parade.","Because the storm intensified officials, canceled the parade.","Because, the storm intensified, officials canceled the parade."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"When a dependent clause opens the sentence, a comma follows it. The correct version places one comma after \"intensified.\" The others drop that comma, add a wrong comma after \"Because,\" or split the subject from its verb."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Using Commas with Introductory Words","difficulty":3,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["Although she had studied for weeks, she still felt nervous before the exam.","Although she had studied for weeks she still felt nervous before the exam.","Although she had studied, for weeks she still felt nervous before the exam.","Although, she had studied for weeks, she still felt nervous before the exam."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The introductory dependent clause \"Although she had studied for weeks\" is followed by a single comma. The other options omit it, add a stray comma after \"Although,\" or break up the clause incorrectly."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Using Commas to Join Clauses Together","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["The rain finally stopped, and the children ran outside.","The rain finally stopped and the children ran outside.","The rain finally stopped and, the children ran outside.","The rain finally stopped, the children ran outside."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Two independent clauses joined by the coordinating conjunction \"and\" take a comma before the conjunction. Omitting it creates a missing-comma error, joining with only a comma creates a comma splice, and placing the comma after \"and\" is misplaced."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Using Commas to Join Clauses Together","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["The team practiced all season, but they lost the championship.","The team practiced all season but they lost the championship.","The team practiced all season but, they lost the championship.","The team practiced all season, they lost the championship."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"A comma belongs before \"but\" when it joins two independent clauses. The second option omits the required comma, the third is a comma splice with no conjunction, and the fourth misplaces the comma after \"but.\""},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Using Commas to Join Clauses Together","difficulty":3,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["Maria wanted to study abroad, so she saved money for a year.","Maria wanted to study abroad so she saved money for a year.","Maria wanted to study abroad so, she saved money for a year.","Maria wanted to study abroad, she saved money for a year."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The coordinating conjunction \"so\" joins two independent clauses, so a comma precedes it. The others drop the comma, create a comma splice, or place the comma after \"so\" instead of before it."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Using Commas with Nonessential Clauses","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["My oldest brother, who lives in Denver, is visiting next week.","My oldest brother who lives in Denver is visiting next week.","My oldest brother who lives in Denver, is visiting next week.","My oldest brother, who lives in Denver is visiting next week."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"\"who lives in Denver\" adds extra information about an already identified brother, so it is set off with a pair of commas. Using no commas or only one comma fails to enclose the nonessential clause properly."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Using Commas with Nonessential Clauses","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["The novel, which won several awards, was translated into many languages.","The novel which won several awards was translated into many languages.","The novel which won several awards, was translated into many languages.","The novel, which won several awards was translated into many languages."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The clause beginning with \"which\" is nonessential and must be enclosed by two commas. The remaining options either omit both commas or supply only one, leaving the clause incorrectly punctuated."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Using Commas with Nonessential Clauses","difficulty":3,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["Jupiter, the largest planet in the solar system, has dozens of moons.","Jupiter the largest planet in the solar system has dozens of moons.","Jupiter the largest planet in the solar system, has dozens of moons.","Jupiter, the largest planet in the solar system has dozens of moons."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The appositive \"the largest planet in the solar system\" renames Jupiter and is nonessential, so it is set off by two commas. The other versions use no commas or only one, failing to enclose the appositive."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Commas Separating Adjectives","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["It was a long, tiring journey.","It was a long tiring journey.","It was, a long tiring journey.","It was a long, tiring, journey."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"\"Long\" and \"tiring\" are coordinate adjectives that equally modify \"journey,\" so a comma separates them. No comma goes between the last adjective and the noun, and none belongs after \"was.\""},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Commas Separating Adjectives","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["They climbed a steep, rocky trail.","They climbed a steep rocky trail.","They climbed a steep rocky, trail.","They climbed a steep, rocky, trail."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"\"Steep\" and \"rocky\" are coordinate adjectives, so a comma separates them. Omitting that comma is an error, and placing a comma between an adjective and the noun \"trail\" is also incorrect."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Commas Separating Adjectives","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["A cold, damp wind blew across the field.","A cold damp wind blew across the field.","A cold damp, wind blew across the field.","A cold, damp, wind blew across the field."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"\"Cold\" and \"damp\" are coordinate adjectives separated by a comma. The other options omit the needed comma or insert a comma between the final adjective and the noun \"wind.\""},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Using Commas in a Series","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["We packed sandwiches, fruit, and water for the trip.","We packed sandwiches fruit, and water for the trip.","We packed, sandwiches, fruit, and water for the trip.","We packed sandwiches, fruit and, water for the trip."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Items in a series are separated by commas. The correct version places commas between each item. The others omit the comma after \"sandwiches,\" misplace a comma after \"and,\" or wrongly insert a comma after the verb \"packed.\""},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Using Commas in a Series","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["The recipe calls for flour, sugar, butter, and eggs.","The recipe calls for flour, sugar butter, and eggs.","The recipe calls for flour, sugar, butter and, eggs.","The recipe calls for flour sugar, butter, and eggs."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Each item in the four-item series is separated by a comma. The other options drop a required comma between two items or misplace the comma after \"and\" instead of before it."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Using Commas in a Series","difficulty":3,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["Our tour included Rome, Paris, and Madrid.","Our tour, included Rome, Paris, and Madrid.","Our tour included Rome, Paris and, Madrid.","Our tour included Rome Paris, and Madrid."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The three cities form a series with commas separating them. The other options add a wrong comma after \"tour,\" omit the comma between \"Rome\" and \"Paris,\" or misplace the comma after \"and.\""},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Correctly Punctuating Quotations","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence correctly punctuates the quotation?","options":["\"Let's meet at noon,\" Carlos suggested.","\"Let's meet at noon.\" Carlos suggested.","\"Let's meet at noon\", Carlos suggested.","\"Let's meet at noon\" Carlos suggested."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"When a dialogue tag follows the quotation, a comma belongs inside the closing quotation marks. Option 0 is correct. Option 1 places the comma outside the quotation marks. Option 2 ends the quotation with a period, leaving \"Carlos suggested\" as a fragment. Option 3 omits the comma needed before the tag."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Correctly Punctuating Quotations","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence is correctly punctuated?","options":["\"Where are you going\"? he asked.","\"Where are you going?\" he asked.","\"Where are you going?,\" he asked.","\"Where are you going\" he asked?"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The quoted material is itself a question, so the question mark goes inside the quotation marks, and no additional comma is used. Option 0 is correct. Option 1 places the question mark outside the quotation marks. Option 2 adds an incorrect comma after the question mark. Option 3 leaves the quotation unpunctuated and misplaces the question mark on the tag."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Correctly Punctuating Quotations","difficulty":3,"stem":"Which sentence is correctly punctuated?","options":["Did the coach really call the loss \"a blessing in disguise?\"","Did the coach really call the loss \"a blessing in disguise\"?","Did the coach really call the loss, \"a blessing in disguise\"?","Did the coach really call the loss \"a blessing in disguise.\""],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The quoted phrase is a statement, but the whole sentence is a question, so the question mark belongs outside the closing quotation marks. Option 0 is correct. Option 1 wrongly places the question mark inside the quotation marks. Option 2 inserts an unnecessary comma after \"loss.\" Option 3 ends a question with a period placed inside the quotation marks."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Correct Use of Colons","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence uses a colon correctly?","options":["We need three things; water, food, and shelter.","We need: water, food, and shelter.","We need three things: water, food, and shelter.","We need three things, water, food, and shelter."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"A colon introducing a list must follow an independent clause. Option 0 is correct. Option 1 places the colon right after the verb \"need,\" so no complete clause precedes it. Option 2 misuses a semicolon, which cannot introduce a list. Option 3 uses only a comma, which fails to set off the list and blurs the count."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Correct Use of Colons","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence uses a colon correctly?","options":["Bring the essentials, a flashlight, water, and a map.","Bring: a flashlight, water, and a map.","Bring the essentials: a flashlight, water, and a map.","Bring the essentials; a flashlight, water, and a map."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"\"Bring the essentials\" is a complete imperative clause, so a colon may introduce the list. Option 0 is correct. Option 1 places the colon after the verb, with no full clause before it. Option 2 uses only a comma, which does not properly introduce the list. Option 3 uses a semicolon before a list of phrases, which is not an independent clause."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Correct Use of Colons","difficulty":3,"stem":"Which sentence uses a colon correctly?","options":["The verdict was clear the defendant was not guilty.","The verdict was clear, the defendant was not guilty.","The verdict was clear: the defendant was not guilty.","The verdict was clear: but the defendant was not guilty."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"A colon can join two independent clauses when the second explains the first. Option 0 is correct. Option 1 joins two independent clauses with only a comma, creating a comma splice. Option 2 fuses the two clauses with no punctuation, creating a run-on. Option 3 places a coordinating conjunction after the colon, which is incorrect."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Correct Use of Parentheses","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence uses parentheses correctly?","options":["The museum (which opened in 1920) is free on Sundays).","The museum (which opened in 1920,) is free on Sundays.","The museum, (which opened in 1920) is free on Sundays.","The museum (which opened in 1920) is free on Sundays."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Parentheses enclose the nonessential phrase, and no extra punctuation is added around them here. Option 0 is correct. Option 1 inserts a needless comma before the opening parenthesis. Option 2 places a comma inside the closing parenthesis. Option 3 adds a stray second closing parenthesis."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Correct Use of Parentheses","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence is punctuated correctly?","options":["We left early (the storm was approaching).","We left early (the storm was approaching.)","We left early (the storm was approaching)","We left early, (the storm was approaching)."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"When a parenthetical falls at the end of a sentence, the terminal period goes outside the closing parenthesis. Option 0 is correct. Option 1 places the period inside the parentheses. Option 2 adds an unnecessary comma before the opening parenthesis. Option 3 omits the sentence-ending period entirely."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Correct Use of Parentheses","difficulty":3,"stem":"Which sentence uses parentheses correctly?","options":["After the meeting (which ran late) we grabbed dinner.","After the meeting, (which ran late) we grabbed dinner.","After the meeting (which ran late,) we grabbed dinner.","After the meeting (which ran late), we grabbed dinner."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The introductory element needs a comma, which belongs outside and after the closing parenthesis. Option 0 is correct. Option 1 places the comma inside the parentheses. Option 2 puts the comma before the parenthetical rather than after it. Option 3 omits the comma the introductory phrase requires."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Types of Sentences","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which of the following is a compound sentence?","options":["The rain stopped after the storm passed.","The rain finally stopped.","When the rain stopped, the children cheered.","The rain stopped, and the sun appeared."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"A compound sentence joins two independent clauses with a comma and a coordinating conjunction. Option 0 has two independent clauses joined by \"and,\" so it is compound. Options 1 and 2 each contain a dependent clause, making them complex. Option 3 is a single independent clause, making it simple."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Types of Sentences","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which of the following is a complex sentence?","options":["She was tired and hungry.","She finished the race; she was exhausted.","She was tired, but she finished the race.","Although she was tired, she finished the race."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"A complex sentence has one independent clause and at least one dependent clause. Option 0 pairs the dependent clause \"Although she was tired\" with an independent clause, so it is complex. Option 1 joins two independent clauses, making it compound. Option 2 is a single independent clause, making it simple. Option 3 links two independent clauses with a semicolon, making it compound."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Types of Sentences","difficulty":3,"stem":"Which of the following is a compound-complex sentence?","options":["The game was canceled, and we went home.","Because it rained, the game was canceled.","Because it rained, the game was canceled, and we went home.","The game was canceled after the long storm."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"A compound-complex sentence has two independent clauses and at least one dependent clause. Option 0 has the dependent clause \"Because it rained\" plus two independent clauses joined by \"and,\" so it is compound-complex. Option 1 is compound. Option 2 is complex. Option 3 is a simple sentence with a prepositional phrase."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Identifying Correct Sentence Structure","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which of the following is a complete, correctly structured sentence?","options":["The hikers reached the summit they ate lunch.","The hikers reached the summit before noon.","The hikers reached the summit, they ate lunch.","Because the hikers reached the summit before noon."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Option 0 is a complete sentence with a subject and verb. Option 1 is a fragment because the subordinating conjunction \"Because\" leaves the thought incomplete. Option 2 joins two independent clauses with only a comma, creating a comma splice. Option 3 fuses two independent clauses with no punctuation, creating a run-on."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Identifying Correct Sentence Structure","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence is correctly structured, with no run-on, comma splice, or fragment?","options":["The store closed early, we ordered takeout.","Since the store closed early.","The store closed early we ordered takeout.","The store closed early, so we ordered takeout."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Option 0 correctly joins two independent clauses with a comma and the coordinating conjunction \"so.\" Option 1 joins them with only a comma, creating a comma splice. Option 2 has no punctuation between the clauses, creating a run-on. Option 3 is a dependent-clause fragment."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Identifying Correct Sentence Structure","difficulty":3,"stem":"Which of the following is correctly structured?","options":["The novel that she recommended last week.","The novel that she recommended kept me awake, I could not stop reading.","The novel that she recommended kept me awake I could not stop reading.","The novel that she recommended kept me awake all night."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Option 0 is a complete sentence; \"that she recommended\" is a relative clause modifying \"novel,\" and \"kept me awake all night\" supplies the predicate. Option 1 is a fragment with no main verb for \"novel.\" Option 2 is a comma splice joining two independent clauses with only a comma. Option 3 is a run-on with no punctuation between the clauses."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Subject-Verb Agreement","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence has correct subject-verb agreement?","options":["The box of chocolates are on the table.","The box of chocolates were on the table.","The box of chocolates have been on the table.","The box of chocolates is on the table."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The subject is the singular noun \"box\"; \"of chocolates\" is a prepositional phrase that does not change the verb. Option 0 correctly uses the singular \"is.\" Options 1, 2, and 3 all use plural verbs (\"are,\" \"were,\" \"have been\") that incorrectly agree with \"chocolates\" rather than \"box.\"","rationale":{"takeaway": "Strip the prepositional phrase and the subject is 'box.'", "whyCorrect": "'The box of chocolates is on the table' matches the singular subject with the singular verb 'is.'", "distractors": {"0": "'are' agrees with 'chocolates,' a noun inside the phrase, not the subject.", "1": "'were' makes the same error in past tense.", "2": "'have been' is likewise plural."}, "commonMistake": "Choosing by ear. Three plural verbs sound natural next to 'chocolates,' which is exactly why the phrase was put there."}},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Subject-Verb Agreement","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence has correct subject-verb agreement?","options":["Each of the players deserve a medal.","Both of the players deserves a medal.","Neither of the players deserve a medal.","Each of the players deserves a medal."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The indefinite pronoun \"Each\" is singular and takes a singular verb. Option 0 correctly uses \"deserves.\" Option 1 wrongly pairs singular \"Each\" with plural \"deserve.\" Option 2 pairs plural \"Both\" with singular \"deserves.\" Option 3 pairs singular \"Neither\" with plural \"deserve.\"","rationale":{"takeaway": "'Each' is singular; 'both' is plural.", "whyCorrect": "'Each of the players deserves a medal' pairs singular 'Each' with singular 'deserves.'", "distractors": {"0": "'Each ... deserve' pairs a singular subject with a plural verb.", "1": "'Both' is plural and needs 'deserve,' not 'deserves.'", "2": "'Neither' is singular and needs 'deserves.'"}, "commonMistake": "Treating each, both, and neither alike. Both is the only plural of the three, so it takes the opposite verb form from the other two."}},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Subject-Verb Agreement","difficulty":3,"stem":"Which sentence has correct subject-verb agreement?","options":["Neither the manager nor the employees was aware of the change.","Neither the employees nor the manager were aware of the change.","Neither the manager or the employees were aware of the change.","Neither the manager nor the employees were aware of the change."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"With \"neither...nor,\" the verb agrees with the nearer subject. In option 0, the nearer subject \"employees\" is plural, so \"were\" is correct. Option 1 uses singular \"was\" with the plural nearer subject. Option 2 uses plural \"were\" when the nearer subject \"manager\" is singular. Option 3 incorrectly pairs \"Neither\" with \"or\" instead of \"nor.\"","rationale":{"takeaway": "With 'neither ... nor,' the verb agrees with the subject closer to it.", "whyCorrect": "In 'Neither the manager nor the employees were aware,' 'employees' is nearer the verb, so the plural 'were' is correct.", "distractors": {"0": "'employees was' mismatches the nearer plural subject.", "1": "Here 'manager' is nearer, so it would need 'was,' not 'were.'", "2": "'Neither ... or' is the wrong pairing; neither takes nor."}, "commonMistake": "Applying one rule to every neither sentence. Alone, 'neither' is singular; in the 'neither ... nor' pair, proximity decides."}},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Misplaced and Dangling Modifiers","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence is free of a misplaced or dangling modifier?","options":["Walking to school, a wallet was found on the sidewalk.","Walking to school, the wallet on the sidewalk caught my eye.","Walking to school, the sidewalk had a wallet on it.","Walking to school, I found a wallet on the sidewalk."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The opening phrase \"Walking to school\" must modify the person doing the walking. Option 0 correctly follows it with \"I.\" Option 1 dangles because the subject \"a wallet\" was not walking. Option 2 dangles because \"the sidewalk\" was not walking. Option 3 dangles because the subject \"the wallet\" was not walking."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Misplaced and Dangling Modifiers","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence is correctly constructed, with no dangling modifier?","options":["After studying all night, Maria's notes were finally organized.","After studying all night, Maria felt confident about the exam.","After studying all night, confidence came easily to Maria.","After studying all night, the exam seemed easy to Maria."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The phrase \"After studying all night\" must modify whoever studied. Option 0 correctly follows it with \"Maria.\" Option 1 dangles because \"the exam\" did not study. Option 2 dangles because the subject \"Maria's notes\" did not study. Option 3 dangles because the subject \"confidence\" did not study."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"conventions","subtopic":"Misplaced and Dangling Modifiers","difficulty":3,"stem":"Which sentence is free of a misplaced or dangling modifier?","options":["We spotted a family of bighorn sheep driving through the canyon.","A family of bighorn sheep was spotted driving through the canyon by us.","Driving through the canyon, a family of bighorn sheep was spotted.","Driving through the canyon, we spotted a family of bighorn sheep."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The modifier \"Driving through the canyon\" should describe the people in the car. Option 0 correctly follows it with \"we.\" Option 1 misplaces the phrase so it seems to describe the sheep driving. Option 2 dangles because the subject \"a family of bighorn sheep\" was not driving. Option 3 likewise places \"driving through the canyon\" next to the sheep, implying the sheep were driving."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Identifying Genre","difficulty":1,"stem":"Read the passage: \"The salt marsh exhales at dawn, and the heron lifts its question mark of a neck against a sky the color of old pewter.\" To which genre does this passage most likely belong?","options":["Legal contract","Technical manual","News report","Poetry or literary prose"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The figurative language ('exhales,' 'question mark of a neck') and imagery signal literary/poetic writing. Technical manuals, news reports, and contracts use plain, factual language without metaphor."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Identifying Genre","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage: \"WHEREAS the Tenant agrees to remit payment no later than the fifth day of each calendar month, and WHEREAS failure to do so shall incur a late fee of five percent...\" This passage is an example of which genre?","options":["Legal or contractual writing","Folk tale","Persuasive essay","Personal memoir"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The formal terms 'WHEREAS,' 'Tenant,' and 'shall incur' are conventions of legal and contractual documents. The other genres would not use binding, clause-based language."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Identifying Genre","difficulty":3,"stem":"A text begins: \"Captain's log, stardate 4521.3. We have entered the asteroid belt, and the navigation array is failing. If the colonists are to survive, I must reroute power from the cryo-bays before the next solar flare.\" This passage best fits which genre?","options":["Instructional how-to guide","Investigative journalism","Science fiction","Historical biography"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Invented future elements ('stardate,' 'cryo-bays,' 'solar flare' affecting a colony ship) are hallmarks of science fiction. A biography or journalism would report real events, and a how-to guide would give steps."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Matching Sentences to Types of Writing","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which sentence is an example of expository writing?","options":["She wondered if the letter would ever arrive.","You absolutely must vote in this election to protect our future.","Photosynthesis is the process by which plants convert sunlight into chemical energy.","The thunder rolled like a thousand drums across the valley."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Expository writing informs or explains a fact or process, as in the definition of photosynthesis. The first is descriptive, the third is persuasive, and the fourth is narrative."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Matching Sentences to Types of Writing","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence best represents persuasive writing?","options":["The old clock ticked softly in the empty hallway.","Switching to reusable bags is the single most responsible choice a shopper can make.","Water boils at 100 degrees Celsius at sea level.","The recipe requires two cups of flour and one egg."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Persuasive writing urges the reader toward an opinion or action, calling reusable bags the 'most responsible choice.' The others are expository (recipe, boiling point) or descriptive (the clock)."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Matching Sentences to Types of Writing","difficulty":3,"stem":"A writer wants a sentence that is purely descriptive, conveying sensory detail without telling a story or arguing a point. Which sentence fits best?","options":["Therefore, the committee should approve the budget at once.","Frost feathered the windowpane in delicate, silver veins.","First, preheat the oven to 375 degrees.","After he left, nothing in the house was ever the same."],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Descriptive writing paints a sensory picture, as the frost 'feathered... in silver veins.' The first is expository/instructional, the third is persuasive, and the fourth advances a narrative."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Identifying Intended Audience","difficulty":1,"stem":"Read the passage: \"Remember to wash your hands with soap and sing the alphabet song twice so the germs go down the drain!\" Who is the most likely intended audience?","options":["Hospital surgeons","Corporate executives","Young children","University researchers"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"Simple instructions tied to a song and the playful tone target young children. Surgeons, executives, and researchers would receive more technical or formal guidance."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Identifying Intended Audience","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the passage: \"Before titrating the analyte, ensure the burette is rinsed with the standardized solution to avoid concentration errors in your endpoint reading.\" Who is the most likely intended audience?","options":["Chemistry lab students or technicians","Restaurant patrons","General newspaper readers","Elementary school students"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Technical terms like 'titrating,' 'analyte,' and 'burette' assume a reader trained in laboratory chemistry. The other audiences would not be expected to know this vocabulary."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Identifying Intended Audience","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the passage: \"Whether you are downsizing after retirement or simply tired of yard work, our maintenance-free condos let you trade the lawnmower for a morning coffee on your private balcony.\" Who is the primary intended audience?","options":["Construction contractors","Commercial real estate investors","Older adults considering a lower-maintenance home","First-time apartment renters in their twenties"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"References to 'downsizing after retirement' and trading yard work for leisure clearly target older adults seeking less upkeep. Young renters, investors, and contractors are not addressed by these appeals."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Identifying Appropriate Language for Intended Audience/Tone","difficulty":1,"stem":"A student is writing a formal cover letter to apply for a job. Which sentence uses language appropriate for that tone?","options":["I am writing to express my strong interest in the marketing associate position.","Hey, I'd be super pumped to work for you guys!","This job sounds awesome and I really wanna do it.","Gimme a shot and you won't regret it, I promise."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"A formal cover letter requires professional, polished language, as in 'I am writing to express my strong interest.' The other options use slang and casual phrasing inappropriate for the context."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Identifying Appropriate Language for Intended Audience/Tone","difficulty":2,"stem":"A writer wants to maintain an objective, neutral tone in a science article. Which sentence best fits that tone?","options":["Sloths conserve energy by moving slowly and digesting food over several days.","Everyone adores sloths because they are the cutest animals alive.","The shockingly lazy sloth barely moves, which is honestly ridiculous.","You won't believe how unbelievably slow these amazing creatures are!"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"A neutral, objective tone reports facts without emotional or evaluative language, as in describing how sloths conserve energy. The others insert opinion ('lazy,' 'cutest,' 'unbelievably')."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Identifying Appropriate Language for Intended Audience/Tone","difficulty":3,"stem":"A nurse must explain a diagnosis to a worried patient with no medical background, using a reassuring and clear tone. Which sentence is most appropriate?","options":["Your echocardiogram revealed reduced left ventricular ejection fraction consistent with systolic dysfunction.","Cardiac output is compromised; prognosis depends on adherence to the pharmacological regimen.","Honestly, your heart's kind of a mess, so good luck with that.","Your heart isn't pumping as strongly as it should right now, but there are treatments that can help, and we will go through them together."],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Plain, warm language that explains the condition and offers support fits a worried layperson. The first and third are too technical, and the fourth is dismissive and unprofessional."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Stages of the Writing Process","difficulty":1,"stem":"During which stage of the writing process does a writer generate ideas, brainstorm, and organize thoughts before composing any sentences?","options":["Editing","Prewriting","Revising","Publishing"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Prewriting is the planning stage where writers brainstorm and organize ideas before drafting. Revising and editing occur after a draft exists, and publishing is the final step."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Stages of the Writing Process","difficulty":2,"stem":"A writer rereads her draft and reorganizes paragraphs, adds a new supporting example, and sharpens her thesis for clarity. Which stage of the writing process is she in?","options":["Proofreading for spelling","Drafting","Prewriting","Revising"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Revising focuses on improving content, organization, and ideas, such as reordering paragraphs and strengthening the thesis. Proofreading addresses only surface errors like spelling, which comes later."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Stages of the Writing Process","difficulty":2,"type":"ORDERED","stem":"Arrange the stages of the writing process in their correct, conventional order from first to last.","options":["Drafting (writing the first version)","Editing and publishing (correcting errors and sharing)","Prewriting (brainstorming and planning)","Revising (improving content and organization)"],"correct":[2,0,3,1],"explanation":"The conventional writing process moves from prewriting to drafting, then revising for content, and finally editing and publishing the polished work."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Parts of a Paragraph","difficulty":1,"stem":"In a well-structured paragraph, which sentence states the main idea that the rest of the paragraph develops?","options":["The topic sentence","The supporting detail","The example","The transition"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The topic sentence presents the paragraph's main idea, which supporting details, transitions, and examples then develop and reinforce."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Parts of a Paragraph","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the paragraph: \"Community gardens offer surprising benefits beyond fresh produce. They give neighbors a shared space to meet and build friendships. They also teach children where food comes from. In short, these gardens grow people as much as plants.\" Which sentence functions as the concluding sentence?","options":["They give neighbors a shared space to meet and build friendships.","Community gardens offer surprising benefits beyond fresh produce.","In short, these gardens grow people as much as plants.","They also teach children where food comes from."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The concluding sentence wraps up the paragraph's idea, and 'In short, these gardens grow people as much as plants' restates the main point. The first is the topic sentence and the middle two are supporting details."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Parts of a Paragraph","difficulty":3,"stem":"A student has written this topic sentence: \"Regular sleep dramatically improves a student's academic performance.\" Which sentence would serve as the strongest supporting detail?","options":["Sleep is a topic that scientists find interesting.","Coffee shops near campus are usually crowded in the morning.","Studies show that students who sleep eight hours score higher on memory tests than those who sleep five.","Many students enjoy staying up late on weekends."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"A strong supporting detail provides specific evidence for the topic sentence, and the study linking eight hours of sleep to higher test scores directly supports the claim. The other options are off-topic or vague."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Identifying Unrelated Sentences","difficulty":1,"stem":"Read the paragraph: (1) The public library recently expanded its hours to better serve the community. (2) It now opens at eight in the morning on weekdays. (3) Many people enjoy grilling burgers at summer barbecues. (4) The longer hours give commuters time to browse before work. Which sentence does NOT belong in the paragraph?","options":["Sentence 4","Sentence 2","Sentence 1","Sentence 3"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Sentences 1, 2, and 4 all concern the library's expanded hours. Sentence 3, about grilling burgers, is unrelated to the paragraph's topic."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Identifying Unrelated Sentences","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the paragraph: (1) Honeybees play a vital role in pollinating the crops we depend on for food. (2) As they gather nectar, pollen sticks to their bodies and spreads from flower to flower. (3) Without this pollination, many fruits and vegetables would fail to grow. (4) The price of gasoline has risen sharply over the past year. Which sentence does NOT belong in the paragraph?","options":["Sentence 4","Sentence 3","Sentence 2","Sentence 1"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Sentences 1, 2, and 3 develop the idea of honeybees and pollination. Sentence 4, about gasoline prices, introduces an unrelated topic."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Identifying Unrelated Sentences","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the paragraph: (1) Marie Curie's research transformed our understanding of radioactivity. (2) She became the first person to win Nobel Prizes in two different sciences. (3) Her notebooks remain so radioactive that they are still stored in lead-lined boxes. (4) Today, many students find chemistry homework difficult and time-consuming. Which sentence does NOT belong in the paragraph?","options":["Sentence 3","Sentence 1","Sentence 2","Sentence 4"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Sentences 1, 2, and 3 all describe Marie Curie's achievements and legacy. Sentence 4, a general comment about students' homework, breaks the paragraph's focus on Curie."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Using Grammar to Enhance Clarity in Writing","difficulty":1,"stem":"Which revision corrects the misplaced modifier in the sentence \"Covered in melted cheese, the waiter served the nachos to the table\"?","options":["The waiter, covered in melted cheese, served the nachos to the table.","Covered in melted cheese, the table served the nachos to the waiter.","The waiter served the nachos, which were covered in melted cheese, to the table.","Covered in melted cheese, the nachos served the waiter to the table."],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The original implies the waiter was covered in cheese. Placing the modifier next to 'nachos' clarifies that the nachos were covered in cheese, enhancing clarity."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Using Grammar to Enhance Clarity in Writing","difficulty":2,"stem":"Which sentence uses parallel structure correctly for clarity?","options":["On weekends, Mara enjoys hiking, swimming, and biking.","On weekends, Mara enjoys to hike, swimming, and bikes.","On weekends, Mara enjoys hiking, to swim, and biking.","On weekends, Mara enjoys hiking, to swim, and she bikes."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"Parallel structure requires items in a list to share the same grammatical form. 'Hiking, swimming, and biking' keeps all three as gerunds, while the others mix forms and reduce clarity."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"knowledge-language","subtopic":"Using Grammar to Enhance Clarity in Writing","difficulty":3,"stem":"The sentence \"When the manager spoke to the new employee, she said she would receive a raise\" is unclear. Which revision removes the ambiguous pronoun reference?","options":["The manager told the new employee that the employee would receive a raise.","When the manager spoke to the new employee, she said that she would receive a raise.","When she spoke to her, she said she would receive a raise.","She told her that she would receive a raise soon."],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The original 'she' could refer to either woman. Naming the parties directly ('The manager told the new employee that the employee would receive a raise') removes the ambiguity and clarifies who gets the raise."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"vocabulary","subtopic":"Using Prefixes to Determine Word Meaning","difficulty":1,"stem":"The prefix in the word \"circumnavigate\" means \"around.\" Based on this, what does it mean to circumnavigate an island?","options":["To travel all the way around the island","To build a settlement on the island","To travel directly across the island","To study the wildlife of the island"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The prefix circum- means \"around,\" and the root navigate means \"to travel by water.\" To circumnavigate an island is to travel all the way around it."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"vocabulary","subtopic":"Using Prefixes to Determine Word Meaning","difficulty":2,"stem":"The prefix \"mal-\" means \"bad\" or \"badly.\" Which word uses this prefix to describe something that is poorly nourished?","options":["Malfunction","Malnourished","Malicious","Maladjusted"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"Mal- means \"bad\" or \"badly,\" and \"nourished\" relates to feeding. \"Malnourished\" therefore means badly or poorly nourished. The other options use mal- but do not refer to nourishment."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"vocabulary","subtopic":"Using Prefixes to Determine Word Meaning","difficulty":3,"stem":"The prefix \"ambi-\" means \"both.\" Using this knowledge, what is the most likely meaning of \"ambivalent\" in the sentence: \"She felt ambivalent about the move, eager for the adventure yet sad to leave home\"?","options":["Entirely indifferent and uninterested","Completely opposed to the idea","Firmly decided and confident","Having two opposing feelings at the same time"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"Ambi- means \"both.\" Ambivalent describes holding both feelings at once, which the sentence confirms by naming eagerness and sadness together."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"vocabulary","subtopic":"Using Suffixes to Determine Word Meaning","difficulty":1,"stem":"The suffix \"-ology\" means \"the study of.\" What does \"seismology\" most likely mean?","options":["The fear of earthquakes","A tool for measuring earthquakes","The study of earthquakes","The study of weather"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The suffix -ology means \"the study of,\" and the root seismo- refers to earthquakes. Seismology is the study of earthquakes."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"vocabulary","subtopic":"Using Suffixes to Determine Word Meaning","difficulty":2,"stem":"The suffix \"-phobia\" means \"fear of.\" In the word \"agoraphobia,\" the root \"agora\" refers to an open public space. What does agoraphobia describe?","options":["A love of open public gatherings","The study of public marketplaces","A fear of being alone indoors","A fear of open or crowded public spaces"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The suffix -phobia means \"fear of,\" and agora refers to an open public space. Agoraphobia is the fear of open or crowded public spaces."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"vocabulary","subtopic":"Using Suffixes to Determine Word Meaning","difficulty":3,"stem":"The suffix \"-fy\" means \"to make or cause to become.\" Based on this, what does \"solidify\" mean?","options":["To make something solid","The state of being solid","One who studies solids","To make something larger"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The suffix -fy means \"to make or cause to become,\" so solidify means to make something solid. Note that -ity, not -fy, would indicate the state of being solid."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"vocabulary","subtopic":"Using Common Root Words to Determine Word Meaning","difficulty":1,"stem":"The root \"aqua\" means \"water.\" What is the most likely meaning of an \"aqueduct,\" given that \"duct\" means \"to lead or carry\"?","options":["A tank used to raise fish","A boat designed for shallow rivers","A channel built to carry water","A device that measures rainfall"],"correct":[2],"explanation":"The root aqua means \"water\" and duct means \"to lead or carry.\" An aqueduct is a structure that carries water from one place to another."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"vocabulary","subtopic":"Using Common Root Words to Determine Word Meaning","difficulty":2,"stem":"The root \"dict\" means \"to speak\" or \"to say.\" Using this root, what does it mean to \"contradict\" someone?","options":["To speak against or say the opposite of what they said","To write down everything they say","To praise what they have said","To repeat exactly what they said"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The root dict means \"to speak,\" and the prefix contra- means \"against.\" To contradict is to speak against or assert the opposite of what was said."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"vocabulary","subtopic":"Using Common Root Words to Determine Word Meaning","difficulty":3,"stem":"The root \"spect\" means \"to look\" or \"to see.\" In the sentence \"The auditor reviewed the records with great circumspection,\" what does the root suggest about circumspection?","options":["Carefully looking at all sides before acting","Loudly speaking about the findings","Permanently removing the records","Quickly approving without review"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The root spect means \"to look,\" and circum- means \"around.\" Circumspection involves looking carefully around at all sides, meaning cautious, thorough attention before acting."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"vocabulary","subtopic":"Use Context Clues to Determine Word Meaning","difficulty":1,"stem":"Read the sentence: \"Because the trail was so arduous, the hikers stopped often to rest their aching legs.\" What does \"arduous\" most likely mean?","options":["Requiring great effort; difficult","Short in distance","Smooth and easy","Pleasant and scenic"],"correct":[0],"explanation":"The context clue \"stopped often to rest their aching legs\" signals that the trail demanded great effort. Arduous means difficult and strenuous."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"vocabulary","subtopic":"Use Context Clues to Determine Word Meaning","difficulty":2,"stem":"Read the sentence: \"Unlike his gregarious sister, who chatted with every guest, Marcus preferred to read quietly in the corner.\" What does \"gregarious\" most likely mean?","options":["Shy and withdrawn","Generous with money","Strict and demanding","Sociable and fond of company"],"correct":[3],"explanation":"The word \"Unlike\" sets up a contrast between the sister, who chatted with every guest, and Marcus, who stayed quiet. Gregarious means sociable and enjoying the company of others."},
  {"section":"ENGLISH","topic":"vocabulary","subtopic":"Use Context Clues to Determine Word Meaning","difficulty":3,"stem":"Read the sentence: \"The committee's decision was not capricious; every recommendation followed months of careful study and consistent reasoning.\" What does \"capricious\" most likely mean?","options":["Approved by a large majority","Based on sudden, unpredictable whims","Carefully reasoned and consistent","Delayed for a long period of time"],"correct":[1],"explanation":"The sentence says the decision was NOT capricious because it followed careful, consistent reasoning. The negation tells us capricious means the opposite: impulsive and based on sudden, unpredictable whims."},
];
